{"title_page": "Marci Klein", "text_new": "{{short description|American television producer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Marci Klein\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1967|10|21}}\n| birth_place  = \n| occupation   = Television producer\n| years_active = \n| spouse       = {{marriage|Scott Murphy|2000}}\n| children     = 2\n| parents      = [[Calvin Klein]]<br/> Jayne Centre Klein\n| website      = \n}}\n\n'''Marci Klein''' (born October 21, 1967) is an [[United States|American]] [[television producer]] best known for her work on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' and ''[[30 Rock]].'' She has won four [[Emmy Award]]s. She is the daughter of fashion designer [[Calvin Klein]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nKlein is the daughter of fashion designer [[Calvin Klein]], and his first wife, Jayne Centre. She admitted being embarrassed by often seeing her father's name on her boyfriends' underwear.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/parents/former-wife-of/|title=Calvin's ex Kelly Klein to become a mother at 50|website=People|date=August 28, 2007|accessdate=October 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Heymann, C. David |title=American Legacy: The Story of John and Caroline Kennedy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KqNU8dwWlhQC&pg=PA410+|date=10 July 2007|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4165-4638-2|pages=410\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1978, at the age of 10, Marci Klein was kidnapped by her babysitter. After her father paid the ransom, the police were able to track back the kidnappers. The babysitter said that Calvin Klein set up this abduction to get nationwide publicity.<ref>Scott McCabe, [http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/crime-history-daughter-of-calvin-kleinabducted-held-for-ransom/article/17609 Crime History - Daughter of Calvin Klein abducted, held for ransom], ''Washingtonexaminer.com'', 2 February 2010</ref>\n\nKlein grew up in New York City, where she attended the [[Dalton School]]. She graduated from [[Brown University]]. \n\n==Career==\nIn 1989, Klein began a 20-year career at ''Saturday Night Live''. As a producer and head of the show's talent department, Klein discovered a number of future comedy superstars, including [[Tracy Morgan]], [[Jimmy Fallon]], [[Seth Meyers]], [[Will Ferrell]], [[Fred Armisen]], [[Chris Kattan]], [[Darrell Hammond]], [[Sarah Silverman]], [[Kevin James]], [[Jason Sudeikis]], [[Bill Hader]], [[Maya Rudolph]], and [[Ana Gasteyer]].<ref>Itzkoff, Dave (August 22, 2013) [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/25/arts/television/the-god-of-snl-will-see-you-now.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 The God of \u2018SNL\u2019 Will See You Now]. ''New York Times''</ref> She is frequently talked about as a successor to SNL creator and Executive Producer [[Lorne Michaels]].\n\nKlein has been nominated for 14 Emmys, winning four times, once for ''Saturday Night Live's 25th Anniversary Special'' and three times for ''30 Rock''.<ref>[http://www.emmys.com/shows/saturday-night-live-25th-anniversary-special Saturday Night Live: The 25th Anniversary Special | Television Academy]. Emmys.com. Retrieved on December 17, 2016.</ref> She has also been nominated for nine Producers Guild Awards, winning three.\n\nDuring [[Alec Baldwin]]'s 2007 [[Golden Globes]] acceptance speech, he personally thanked Klein and referred to her as \"the greatest producer in the history of broadcast television,\" to which she received an ovation from the audience.\n\nKlein married Scott Murphy in 2000 at the Wainscott Chapel in [[Wainscott, New York]].<ref>[http://www.rexfeatures.com/set/328064 Rex News: \"Calvin Klein at the Wedding of his daughter Marci Klein, Saturday Night Live Producer, to Scott Murphy at Wainscott Chapel in the Hamptons, Long Island, New York\"]. rexfeatures.com (October 30, 2000)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0458885|name=Marci Klein}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090112141559/http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/2009/01/tina_fey200901?currentPage=3 What Tina Fey Wants | vanityfair.com]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Klein, Marci}}\n[[Category:Emerson College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Television producers from California]]\n[[Category:Women television producers]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:University of California, San Diego alumni]]\n[[Category:Kidnapped American children]]\n[[Category:Kidnapped American people]]\n[[Category:Dalton School alumni]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Television producers from New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American television producer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Marci Klein\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1967|10|21}}\n| birth_place  = \n| occupation   = Television producer\n| years_active = \n| spouse       = {{marriage|Scott Murphy|2000}}\n| children     = 2\n| parents      = [[Calvin Klein]]<br/> Jayne Centre Klein\n| website      = \n}}\n\n'''Marci Klein''' (born October 21, 1967) is an [[United States|American]] [[television producer]] best known for her work on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' and ''[[30 Rock]].'' She has won four [[Emmy Award]]s. She is the daughter of fashion designer [[Calvin Klein]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nKlein is the daughter of fashion designer [[Calvin Klein]], and his first wife, Jayne Centre. She admitted being embarrassed by often seeing her father's name on her boyfriends' underwear.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/parents/former-wife-of/|title=Calvin's ex Kelly Klein to become a mother at 50|website=People|date=August 28, 2007|accessdate=October 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Heymann, C. David |title=American Legacy: The Story of John and Caroline Kennedy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KqNU8dwWlhQC&pg=PA410+|date=10 July 2007|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4165-4638-2|pages=410\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1978, at the age of 10, Marci Klein was kidnapped by her babysitter. After her father paid the ransom, the police were able to track back the kidnappers. The babysitter said that Calvin Klein set up this abduction to get nationwide publicity.<ref>Scott McCabe, [http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/crime-history-daughter-of-calvin-kleinabducted-held-for-ransom/article/17609 Crime History - Daughter of Calvin Klein abducted, held for ransom], ''Washingtonexaminer.com'', 2 February 2010</ref>\n\nKlein grew up in New York City, where she attended the [[Dalton School]]. She graduated from [[Brown University]]. \n\n==Career==\nIn 1989, Klein began a 20-year career at ''Saturday Night Live''. As a producer and head of the show's talent department, Klein discovered a number of future comedy superstars, including [[Tracy Morgan]], [[Jimmy Fallon]], [[Seth Meyers]], [[Will Ferrell]], [[Fred Armisen]], [[Chris Kattan]], [[Darrell Hammond]], [[Sarah Silverman]], [[Kevin James]], [[Jason Sudeikis]], [[Bill Hader]], [[Maya Rudolph]], and [[Ana Gasteyer]].<ref>Itzkoff, Dave (August 22, 2013) [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/25/arts/television/the-god-of-snl-will-see-you-now.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 The God of \u2018SNL\u2019 Will See You Now]. ''New York Times''</ref> She is frequently talked about as a successor to SNL creator and Executive Producer [[Lorne Michaels]].\n\nKlein has been nominated for 14 Emmys, winning four times, once for ''Saturday Night Live's 25th Anniversary Special'' and three times for ''30 Rock''.<ref>[http://www.emmys.com/shows/saturday-night-live-25th-anniversary-special Saturday Night Live: The 25th Anniversary Special | Television Academy]. Emmys.com. Retrieved on December 17, 2016.</ref> She has also been nominated for nine Producers Guild Awards, winning three.\n\nDuring [[Alec Baldwin]]'s 2007 [[Golden Globes]] acceptance speech, he personally thanked Klein and referred to her as \"the greatest producer in the history of broadcast television,\" to which she received an ovation from the audience.\n\nKlein married Scott Murphy in 2000 at the Wainscott Chapel in [[Wainscott, New York]].<ref>[http://www.rexfeatures.com/set/328064 Rex News: \"Calvin Klein at the Wedding of his daughter Marci Klein, Saturday Night Live Producer, to Scott Murphy at Wainscott Chapel in the Hamptons, Long Island, New York\"]. rexfeatures.com (October 30, 2000)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0458885|name=Marci Klein}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090112141559/http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/2009/01/tina_fey200901?currentPage=3 What Tina Fey Wants | vanityfair.com]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Klein, Marci}}\n[[Category:Emerson College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Television producers from California]]\n[[Category:Women television producers]]\n[[Category:Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:University of California, San Diego alumni]]\n[[Category:Kidnapped American children]]\n[[Category:Kidnapped American people]]\n[[Category:Dalton School alumni]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Television producers from New York City]]\n", "name_user": "Aiksu", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marci_Klein"}
{"title_page": "Canberra Coronavirus Field Hospital", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n| name = Coronavirus Field Hospital\n| coordinates = {{coord|-35.34305|149.1018914|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| owner = [[Government of the Australian Capital Territory|ACT Government]]\n| cost = AUD$23 million\n| demolition_date = <!-- or | destruction_date    = -->\n| closing_date = \n| renovation_date = \n| relocated_date = \n| inauguration_date = \n| opened_date = \n| completion_date = \n| est_completion = May 2020\n| stop_date = \n| start_date = \n| groundbreaking_date = April 9, 2020\n| altitude = 603 meters\n| location_country = Australia\n| image = \n| location_city = Canberra\n| address = 123 Kitchner Street, Garran, ACT, Australia\n| location = \n| classification = Hospital\n| building_type = [[Field hospital]]\n| status = Under construction\n| relief = \n| map_dot_mark = \n| map_dot_label = \n| map_size = \n| map_caption = The proposed location of the hospital\n| map_type = Australian Capital Territory\n| image_size = \n| main_contractor = [[Aspen Medical]]\n}}\nThe '''Canberra Coronavirus Field Hospital''' is a temporary hospital under construction in [[Canberra|Canberra, Australia]], created in preparation of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 COVID-19]] [[pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canberraweekly.com.au/garran-oval-to-house-covid-19-ed/|title=Garran Oval to house temporary COVID-19 ED|last=Media|first=Newstate|date=2020-04-08|website=Canberra Weekly|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> The hospital is to be constructed by [[Aspen Medical]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://the-riotact.com/aspen-medical-to-build-covid-19-ed-at-canberra-hospital/367777|title=Aspen Medical to build COVID-19 ED at Canberra Hospital|last=Bushnell|first=Ian|website=The RiotACT|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> a Canberra based company specializing in temporary hospital construction;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aspenmedical.com/health-services/deployable-mobile-hospitals|title=Deployable Mobile Hospitals|date=2013-09-15|website=www.aspenmedical.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> and will be located on [[Garran, Australian Capital Territory|Garran]] Oval northeast of the existing [[Canberra Hospital]] campus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6717214/acts-23m-coronavirus-ed-to-be-built-on-garran-oval/|title=ACT's $23m coronavirus ED to be built on Garran oval|last=Jervis-Bardy|first=Dan|date=2020-04-09|website=The Canberra Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Construction is expected to cost AUD$23 million and be completed sometime in May 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-au/news/coronavirus/dedicated-coronavirus-field-hospital-to-be-constructed-in-canberra-opening-next-month/ar-BB122eiy|title=Dedicated coronavirus field hospital to be constructed in Canberra, opening next month|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> \n\n== History ==\nThe project was announced on 9 April 2020,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/news-articles/temporary-covid-19-emergency-department|title=Temporary COVID-19 Emergency Department|last=Chief Minister|first=Treasury and Economic Development|date=2020-04-09|website=COVID-19|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> at which time 84 patients in Canberra had been diagnosed with COVID-19, of whom 9 were in hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/news-articles/covid-19-update-1-april-2020|title=COVID-19 update \u2013 1 April 2020|last=Chief Minister|first=Treasury and Economic Development|date=2020-04-01|website=COVID-19|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Construction began that day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://the-riotact.com/government-chooses-site-for-temporary-covid-19-ed/369224|title=UPDATED: Temporary COVID-19 ED on Garran Oval will have 200 staff|last=Bushnell|first=Ian|website=The RiotACT|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n== Staff and facility ==\nThe facility will be staffed by 200 nurses, doctors and other medical professionals. Part of the [[Government of the Australian Capital Territory|ACT Government]]'s efforts to triple intensive care capacity from 50 to 170 beds,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6715736/act-to-treble-number-of-icu-beds-ahead-of-winter/|title=ACT to treble number of ICU beds ahead of winter|last=Brewer|first=Lucy Bladen Peter|date=2020-04-08|website=The Canberra Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> it alone expands the city's capacity by up to 50 beds,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-02/act-government-to-build-coronavirus-hospital-by-next-month/12111868|title=Four new cases of COVID-19 in Canberra as plans for emergency hospital expansion announced|last=Lowrey|first=Tom|date=2020-04-02|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> with six of those being [[resuscitation]] bays.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6718024/work-begins-on-temporary-coronavirus-ed-at-garran-oval/|title=Work begins on temporary coronavirus ED at Garran Oval|last=Brown|first=Andrew|date=2020-04-09|website=The Canberra Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> In addition to the hospital, infrastructure like power, water, sewerage, and covered walkways connecting it to Canberra Hospital are to be constructed.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Australia]]\n\n== References ==\n\n<references />\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Australia]]\n[[Category:2020 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in the Australian Capital Territory]]\n[[Category:Hospitals and medical institutions associated with the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 2020]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 2020]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n| name = Coronavirus Field Hospital\n| coordinates = {{coord|-35.34305|149.1018914|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| owner = [[Government of the Australian Capital Territory|ACT Government]]\n| cost = AUD$23 million\n| demolition_date = <!-- or | destruction_date    = -->\n| closing_date = \n| renovation_date = \n| relocated_date = \n| inauguration_date = \n| opened_date = \n| completion_date = \n| est_completion = May 2020\n| stop_date = \n| start_date = \n| groundbreaking_date = April 9, 2020\n| altitude = 603 meters\n| location_country = Australia\n| image = \n| location_city = Canberra\n| address = 123 Kitchner Street, Garran, ACT, Australia\n| location = \n| classification = Hospital\n| building_type = [[Field hospital]]\n| status = Under construction\n| relief = \n| map_dot_mark = \n| map_dot_label = \n| map_size = \n| map_caption = The proposed location of the hospital\n| map_type = Australian Capital Territory\n| image_size = \n| main_contractor = [[Aspen Medical]]\n}}\nThe '''Canberra Coronavirus Field Hospital''' is a temporary hospital under construction in [[Canberra|Canberra, Australia]], created in preparation of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 COVID-19]] [[pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canberraweekly.com.au/garran-oval-to-house-covid-19-ed/|title=Garran Oval to house temporary COVID-19 ED|last=Media|first=Newstate|date=2020-04-08|website=Canberra Weekly|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> The hospital is to be constructed by [[Aspen Medical]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://the-riotact.com/aspen-medical-to-build-covid-19-ed-at-canberra-hospital/367777|title=Aspen Medical to build COVID-19 ED at Canberra Hospital|last=Bushnell|first=Ian|website=The RiotACT|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> a Canberra based company specializing in temporary hospital construction;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aspenmedical.com/health-services/deployable-mobile-hospitals|title=Deployable Mobile Hospitals|date=2013-09-15|website=www.aspenmedical.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> and will be located on [[Garran, Australian Capital Territory|Garran]] Oval northeast of the existing [[Canberra Hospital]] campus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6717214/acts-23m-coronavirus-ed-to-be-built-on-garran-oval/|title=ACT's $23m coronavirus ED to be built on Garran oval|last=Jervis-Bardy|first=Dan|date=2020-04-09|website=The Canberra Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Construction is expected to cost AUD$23 million and be completed sometime in May 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-au/news/coronavirus/dedicated-coronavirus-field-hospital-to-be-constructed-in-canberra-opening-next-month/ar-BB122eiy|title=Dedicated coronavirus field hospital to be constructed in Canberra, opening next month|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> \n\n== History ==\nThe project was announced on 9 April 2020,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/news-articles/temporary-covid-19-emergency-department|title=Temporary COVID-19 Emergency Department|last=Chief Minister|first=Treasury and Economic Development|date=2020-04-09|website=COVID-19|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> at which time 84 patients in Canberra had been diagnosed with COVID-19, of whom 9 were in hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/news-articles/covid-19-update-1-april-2020|title=COVID-19 update \u2013 1 April 2020|last=Chief Minister|first=Treasury and Economic Development|date=2020-04-01|website=COVID-19|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Construction began that day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://the-riotact.com/government-chooses-site-for-temporary-covid-19-ed/369224|title=UPDATED: Temporary COVID-19 ED on Garran Oval will have 200 staff|last=Bushnell|first=Ian|website=The RiotACT|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n== Staff and facility ==\nThe facility will be staffed by 200 nurses, doctors and other medical professionals. Part of the [[Government of the Australian Capital Territory|ACT Government]]'s efforts to triple intensive care capacity from 50 to 170 beds,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6715736/act-to-treble-number-of-icu-beds-ahead-of-winter/|title=ACT to treble number of ICU beds ahead of winter|last=Brewer|first=Lucy Bladen Peter|date=2020-04-08|website=The Canberra Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> it alone expands the city's capacity by up to 50 beds,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-02/act-government-to-build-coronavirus-hospital-by-next-month/12111868|title=Four new cases of COVID-19 in Canberra as plans for emergency hospital expansion announced|last=Lowrey|first=Tom|date=2020-04-02|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> with six of those being [[resuscitation]] bays.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6718024/work-begins-on-temporary-coronavirus-ed-at-garran-oval/|title=Work begins on temporary coronavirus ED at Garran Oval|last=Brown|first=Andrew|date=2020-04-09|website=The Canberra Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> In addition to the hospital, power, water, sewerage, and covered walkways connecting it to Canberra Hospital are to be constructed.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Australia]]\n\n== References ==\n\n<references />\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Australia]]\n[[Category:2020 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in the Australian Capital Territory]]\n[[Category:Hospitals and medical institutions associated with the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 2020]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 2020]]\n", "name_user": "Bravetheif", "label": "safe", "comment": "Wording", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canberra_Coronavirus_Field_Hospital"}
