District of China|districts]], 4 [[county-level city|county-level cities]] and 3 [[County (People's Republic of China)|counties]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:100%;\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"| Map\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\"| <div style=\"position: relative\" class=\"center\">\n{{Image label begin|image=Administrative Division Jinhua.png|width=577|link=}} \n{{Image label|x=360|y=1050|scale=577/2060|text=[[Wucheng District|'''Wucheng''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=730|y=790|scale=577/2060|text=[[Jindong District|'''Jindong''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=610|y=1340|scale=577/2060|text=[[Wuyi County, Jinhua|'''Wuyi<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=850|y=240|scale=577/2060|text=[[Pujiang County, Zhejiang|'''Pujiang<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1730|y=940|scale=577/2060|text=[[Pan'an County|'''Pan'an<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=390|y=590|scale=577/2060|text=[[Lanxi, Zhejiang|'''Lanxi<br>{{small|(city)}}''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1030|y=570|scale=577/2060|text=[[Yiwu|'''Yiwu<br>{{small|(city)}}''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1460|y=680|scale=577/2060|text=[[Dongyang|'''Dongyang<br>{{small|(city)}}''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1120|y=1110|scale=577/2060|text=[[Yongkang, Zhejiang|'''Yongkang<br>{{small|(city)}}''']]}}\n</div>\n|-\n! align=left          | Subdivision\n! align=left          | [[Simplified Chinese]]\n! align=left          | [[Pinyin]]\n|-\n| align=left | [[Wucheng District]]\n| align=middle | {{lang|zh-Hans|\u5a7a\u57ce\u533a}}\n| align=right| W\u00f9ch\u00e9ng Q\u016b\n|-\n| align=left | [[Jindong District]]\n| align=middle | {{lang|zh-Hans|\u91d1\u4e1c\u533a}}\n| align=right| J\u012bnd\u014dng Q\u016b\n|-\n| align=left | [[Lanxi, Zhejiang|Lanxi]]\n| align=middle | {{lang|zh-Hans|\u5170\u6eaa\u5e02}}\n| align=right| L\u00e1nx\u012b Sh\u00ec\n|-\n| align=left | [[Yongkang, Zhejiang|Yongkang]]\n| align=middle | {{lang|zh-Hans|\u6c38\u5eb7\u5e02}}\n| align=right| Y\u01d2ngk\u0101ng Sh\u00ec\n|-\n| align=left | [[Yiwu]]\n| align=middle | {{lang|zh-Hans|\u4e49\u4e4c\u5e02}}\n| align=right| Y\u00ecw\u016b Sh\u00ec\n|-\n| align=left | [[Dongyang]]\n| align=middle | {{lang|zh-Hans|\u4e1c\u9633\u5e02}}\n| align=right| D\u014dngy\u00e1ng Sh\u00ec\n|-\n| align=left | [[Wuyi County, Jinhua|Wuyi County]]\n| align=middle | {{lang|zh-Hans|\u6b66\u4e49\u53bf}}\n| align=right| W\u01d4y\u00ec Xi\u00e0n\n|-\n| align=left | [[Pujiang County, Zhejiang|Pujiang County]]\n| align=middle | {{lang|zh-Hans|\u6d66\u6c5f\u53bf}}\n| align=right| P\u01d4ji\u0101ng Xi\u00e0n\n|-\n| align=left | [[Pan'an County]]\n| align=middle | {{lang|zh-Hans|\u78d0\u5b89\u53bf}}\n| align=right| P\u00e1n'\u0101n Xi\u00e0n\n|}\n\nThese are further divided into 191 [[Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China#Township level|township-level divisions]], including 107 [[town of China|towns]], 73 [[Township (People's Republic of China)|townships]] and 11 [[subdistrict]]s.\n\n==Economy==\nJinhua has a rather flexible economic system with distinctive economic characteristics in different areas.  90% of enterprises are in and about 88% of its [[Gross domestic product|GDP]] are from private sector.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\n===Industry===\n[[File:JNP6120G.jpg|thumb|A bus made by the local [[Jinhua Youngman Vehicle]] factory.]]\nJinhua enjoys an advanced civilian-owned economy, with its industry mainly supported by processing and manufacturing. Leading industries of the city include [[clothing]] and [[Textile industry|textile]], [[Mechanical engineering|mechanics]] and [[electronics]], [[Pharmaceutical industry|pharmacy]] and [[Chemical industry|chemistry]], [[Craft production|manufacturing crafts]], [[Metalworking|metalwork]] processing architecture and [[building material]]s, [[automobile]]-and-[[motorcycle accessories]], [[food processing]], and plastic ware.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\nIndustries are distributed with different characteristics in different counties or county-level cities. For instance, [[Yiwu]] is characterized by its [[Light industry|light-industry]] commodities, [[Yongkang, Zhejiang|Yongkang]] by its [[automobile]]-and-[[motorcycle accessories]] and mechanical and electric tools, [[Dongyang]] by its [[clothing]], architecture and [[Magnet|magnetic materials]], the Jinhua Proper by its pharmacy, construction materials and industrial measures, [[Lanxi, Zhejiang|Lanxi]] by its non-ferrous [[metal]], [[cement]], [[towel]]s and daily chemicals, and [[Pujiang County, Zhejiang|Pujiang]] by its [[Textile industry|textile]], lockmaking, and lantern ornaments of [[crystal]]s.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\n====Handicrafts====\nTraditional [[handicraft]]s have been flourishing in Jinhua. The [[wood carving]] and [[bamboo]] weaving in [[Dongyang]], the [[straw plaiting]], lace purling and [[crystal]]s carving in [[Pujiang County, Zhejiang|Pujiang]], and the hardware crafts in [[Yongkang, Zhejiang|Yongkang]], all enjoy a long history of development and the products sell well both abroad and at home.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\n==Transportation==\n[[File:201812 New Jinhua Railway Station.jpg|thumb|[[Jinhua Railway Station]]]]\nMain Railway station: \n[[Jinhua Railway Station]]\n[[Jinhua South Railway Station]]\n[[Yiwu Railway Station]]\n\nJinhua enjoys convenient transportation, being the communications center in southeast China between coastal and inland areas. It is one of the major hubs of landway transportation in the country. The [[Zhejiang]]-[[Jiangxi]], Jinhua-[[Wenzhou]] and Jinhua-[[Qiandaohu]] railways intersect in the city. The [[Hangzhou]]-Jinhua-[[Quzhou]] Expressway, the Jinhua-[[Lishui, Zhejiang|Lishui]]-[[Wenzhou]] Expressway, the No. 330 and 320 National Highways, and other provincial highroads traverse the area. The city aggregation around Jinhua Proper has formed a \"Half-an-Hour's-Ride Economic Circle\", there being merely a 90-minute and a 3-hour journey driving from the city to [[Hangzhou]] and [[Shanghai]] respectively.\n\n[[Yiwu Airport]] offers airlines destined for [[Beijing]], [[Shanghai]], [[Guangzhou]], [[Shenzhen]], [[Xiamen]], [[Qingdao]], and [[Hong Kong]].\n\n== Landmarks ==\n[[Jinhua Architecture Park]], a collection of 17 pavilions designed by Chinese and international architects, set on the banks of the [[Yiwu River]].\n\nChina's Wuju opera theatre\uff0cmainly for opera, ballet, drama, concerts, variety show comprehensive cultural facilities, is one of the landmark building of jinhua city. It is located in Jinhua city east city south street, west of bing rainbow Jin Huajiang north of east road, yiwu, jiang Wu Yijiang sanjiang interchange Dovetail State Park area\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jinhua.gov.cn Government website of Jinhua] {{in lang|zh}}\n*[http://english.jinhua.gov.cn Government website of Jinhua]{{in lang|en}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060803134933/http://community.middlebury.edu/~knutson/pictures/jinhua.html Jinhua First Social Welfare Institute] (orphanage)\n*[http://www.ansi.okstate.edu/breeds/swine/jinhua/ The Jinhua Swine], breeds of livestock\n\n{{Zhejiang topics}}\n{{Zhejiang}}\n{{Jinhua\u2013Wenzhou Railway}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Zhejiang]]\n[[Category:Jinhua| ]]\n", "name_user": "CaradhrasAiguo", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jinhua"}
{"title_page": "Ninja (militia)", "text_new": "{{Infobox War Faction\n|name = Ninjas\n|war = the [[Pool War]]\n|image =File:Des ex- rebelles Ninjas \u00e0 Kinkala, Congo-Brazzaville, le 20 juin 2019.jpg\n|caption = Former Ninja fighters in 2019\n|active =Early 1990s\u20132008; 2016\u20132017\n|leaders = [[Bernard Kol\u00e9las]]<br>[[Frederick Bintsamou|Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bintsangou]] a.k.a. Pastor Ntoumi\n|clans =\n|ideology =\n|headquarters = [[Brazzaville]] (until 1997)<br>[[Pool Department]]\n|area = [[Republic of the Congo]]\n|strength = Estimates of some hundred active; up to 3,000 loosely attached fighters as of 2002<ref name=\"civilians\"/>\n|previous =\n|next =\n|allies = 1993\u201394 conflict: Cobra militia<br>1997\u201399 Civil War: Cocoye militia<br> [[Republic of the Congo]] (1997)\n|opponents = {{flag|Republic of the Congo}}<br> Cocoye militia (1993\u201394)<br> Cobra militia (from 1997)<br> {{flag|Angola}} (1997)<ref name=\"USCIS\"/>\n|battles= \n* [[Republic of the Congo Civil War (1993\u201394)]]\n* [[Republic of the Congo Civil War (1997-99)]]\n* [[2002\u201303 conflict in the Pool Department]]\n* [[Pool War]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Ninjas''' were a [[militia]] in the [[Republic of the Congo]], which participated in numerous wars and insurgencies in the 1990s and 2000s. The Ninjas were formed by the politician [[Bernard Kol\u00e9las]] in the early 1990s and were commanded by [[Frederick Bintsamou|Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bintsamou]], alias Pastor Ntoumi, when Kolelas was in exile.\n\nThe militia fought the supporters of President [[Pascal Lissouba]] in the [[Republic of the Congo Civil War (1993-94)|1993\u201394 Civil War]]. In the [[Republic of the Congo Civil War (1997-99)|1997-99 Civil War]], they allied with Lissouba's forces against the supporters of former President [[Denis Sassou Nguesso]]. After Sassou Nguesso's victory in this Civil War, Ntoumi's Ninjas fought an insurgency against his government in the [[Pool Department]]. The conflict in the Pool escalated in a series of violent clashes in 2002-03, after which the Ninja leadership eventually gave up their armed struggle. Ntoumi announced the disbanding of the Ninjas in 2008 but they resurfaced in 2016, starting the [[Pool War]].\n\n==Character and ideology==\n[[Image:Pastor Ntumi in 2007.jpg|thumb|left|Frederick Bintsamou who is also known as Pastor Ntoumi.]]\nFormed by and originally loyal to [[Bernard Kol\u00e9las]],<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=57515 |title=CONGO: Profile of ex-Prime Minister Bernard Kolelas |date=2005-12-09 |publisher=[[IRIN]] News |accessdate=2010-01-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611170737/http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=57515 |archive-date=2011-06-11 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"kolelas\">{{cite news |title=Congo Ninja leader dies, aged 76 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8359087.stm |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=2009-11-13 |accessdate=2010-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091116145018/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8359087.stm |archive-date=2009-11-16 |url-status=live }}</ref> the Ninja militia was associated with the [[Bakongo]] ethnic group.<ref name=\"civilians\">{{cite web |url=http://www.irinnews.org/report.aspx?reportid=32237 |title=CONGO: Civilians bear brunt of attacks on \"Ninja\" rebels |date=2003-06-03 |publisher=[[IRIN]] News |accessdate=2010-01-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100219011750/http://www.irinnews.org/report.aspx?reportid=32237 |archive-date=2010-02-19 |url-status=live }}</ref> The militia was named after the [[ninja]]s of feudal Japan.<ref name=\"peace\">{{cite news |title=Congo's Ninja rebels burn weapons and pledge peace |first=Christian |last=Tsoumou |url=http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L08473674.htm |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=2007-06-08 |accessdate=2010-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090804102134/http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L08473674.htm |archive-date=2009-08-04 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Ninja field commander, [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bintsamou|Pastor Ntoumi]], has been described as a cult leader<ref name=\"civilians\"/> and a \"messianic pastor\". In 2003, he told a journalist that the [[Holy Spirit]] told him to revive the Ninjas. Ninja militiamen wore the colour purple (symbolizing suffering), and had their hair in dreadlocks. They were reported to believe that the [[apocalypse]] was near.<ref>{{cite news|title=Apocalyptic rebel movement revisits Congo's heart of darkness|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2003/dec/07/congo.rorycarroll|first=Rory|last=Carroll|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=2003-12-07|accessdate=2010-01-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130827192004/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2003/dec/07/congo.rorycarroll|archive-date=2013-08-27|url-status=live}}</ref>  A Ninja leader quoted in a 2000 report claimed that there were \"almost 16,000 ''Ninjas'' in the Pool region\".<ref name=\"USCIS\">{{cite web |url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/country,,USCIS,,COG,456d621e2,3dedffab4,0.html |title=Republic of Congo (Brazzaville): Information on the human rights situation and the Ninja militia |author=[[USCIS|United States Bureau of Citizenship and Immigration Services]] |date=2000-11-14 |accessdate=2010-01-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010075537/http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/country,,USCIS,,COG,456d621e2,3dedffab4,0.html |archivedate=2012-10-10 }}</ref> According to a 2002 news report by [[IRIN]] News, analysts believed Ntoumi commanded \"only a few hundred dedicated fighters and up to 3,000 more loosely attached\", the latter of which were divided and unenthusiastic.<ref name=\"civilians\"/>\n\n== History ==\n=== 1990s: Foundation and Civil War ===\nThe Republic of the Congo, formerly the [[People's Republic of the Congo]] (1970\u20131991), abolished its [[Marxism-Leninism|Marxist-Leninist]] [[one-party state|one-party system]] in 1991. In the new multi-party state, rivaling political leaders formed their own [[militia]]s.<ref name=\"Pennsylvania\"/> [[Denis Sassou Nguesso]], President for much of the one-party era, formed the Cobra militia. [[Pascal Lissouba]], elected President from 1992, formed the Ministerial Guard, or Cocoye militia, and the Zulu militia.<ref name=\"AfricanAffairs\"/> Bernard Kol\u00e9las, leader of the [[Mouvement Congolais pour la D\u00e9mocratie et la D\u00e9veloppement Integral]] (MCDDI) party, formed the Ninjas, recruiting from his party.<ref name=\"profile\"/> After the disputed [[Republic of the Congo parliamentary election, 1993|1993 elections]], violent conflict between the militias began. In this conflict, which lasted until 1994, the Ninjas were allied with Sassou Nguesso's Cobras against Lissouba's Cocoyes.<ref name=\"USCIS\"/> In December 1995, the parties in the conflict signed a peace treaty where they agreed that militiamen aged 18\u201324 would be integrated into the national [[gendarmerie]] and police force.<ref name=\"AfricanAffairs\"/> [[UNESCO]] also launched a plan to disarm the militias.<ref name=\"Pennsylvania\"/> These programs to pacify the country were controversial and unsuccessful, and the militias survived.<ref name=\"Pennsylvania\"/><ref name=\"AfricanAffairs\"/> In peacetime, the morale among the Ninjas suffered due to lack of payments.<ref name=\"AfricanAffairs\"/>\n\nThe [[Republic of the Congo Civil War (1997-99)|Republic of the Congo Civil War]] began in June 1997, when the supporters of President Lissouba (including the [[Military of the Republic of the Congo|Army]] and the Cocoye, Zulu, and Mamba militias) clashed with those of Denis Sassou Nguesso (including the Cobra militia and Sassou Nguesso's sympathizers in the army). Kol\u00e9las, then Mayor of [[Brazzaville]], was initially neutral. The Ninja-controlled districts of Brazzaville, Bacongo and Mak\u00e9l\u00e9k\u00e9l\u00e9 therefore suffered far less casualties than the rest of the city during the first months of the war. In September, Kol\u00e9las sided with Lissouba, and was installed as Prime Minister. The Ninjas thus entered the war on Lissouba's side.<ref name=\"AfricanAffairs\">{{cite journal |last=Bazenguissa-Ganga |first=R\u00e9my |date=January 1999 |title=The Spread of Political Violence in Congo-Brazzaville |journal=[[African Affairs]] |volume=98 |issue=390 |pages=37\u201354 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |jstor=723683 |doi=10.1093/oxfordjournals.afraf.a008001}}</ref> The alliance between the Ninjas and Lissouba's Cocoyes was formalized with the founding of the Mouvement National pour la Liberation du Congo (MNLC),<ref name=\"Pennsylvania\">{{cite web |url=http://www.africa.upenn.edu/Hornet/irin_21799.html |title=CONGO-BRAZZAVILLE: Background on militia groups |first=Ali B. |last=Ali-Dinar |date=1999-02-17 |publisher=[[University of Pennsylvania]]: African Studies Center |accessdate=2010-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628231107/http://www.africa.upenn.edu/Hornet/irin_21799.html |archive-date=2010-06-28 |url-status=live }}</ref> but Ninja leaders such as [[Claude-Ernest Ndalla]] and [[Willy Matsanga]] opposed the alliance and defected with their men to Sassou Nguesso's side.<ref name=\"AfricanAffairs\"/>\n\nSassou Nguesso's forces, supported by [[Angola]], took control of Brazzaville in October 1997, and overthrew Lissouba's government. Sassou Nguesso returned to the presidency.<ref name=\"AfricanAffairs\"/> The Ninjas retreated to the [[Pool Department]] and fought an insurgency against the new government.<ref name=\"Pennsylvania\"/> In 1999, leaders of the Ninjas and Cocoyes signed a ceasefire agreement. Following the ceasefire and defeats against government forces, about 2000 Ninjas and Cocoyes surrendered to the government. The ceasefire agreement was condemned by Kol\u00e9las. By 1999, American sources speculated if Kol\u00e9las and Lissouba were no longer in control of their militias.<ref name=\"USCIS\"/>\n\n=== 2000s: Pool insurgency ===\n[[Image:Pool districts.png|thumb|right|250px|Map showing districts of Pool as well as Pool's location within the Republic of the Congo.]]\nThere were several major clashes between government forces and Ninjas in 2002 and 2003,<ref name=\"timeline\">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/country_profiles/1076836.stm |title=Timeline: Republic of Congo |date=2009-08-01 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=2010-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926162538/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/country_profiles/1076836.stm |archive-date=2009-09-26 |url-status=live }}</ref> resulting in large humanitarian casualties.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=45904 |title=CONGO: UN warns of \"acute humanitarian crisis\" in Pool region |date=2003-09-03 |publisher=[[IRIN]] News |accessdate=2010-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611170706/http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=45904 |archive-date=2011-06-11 |url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2003, Ninja leaders signed agreements with the government to cease hostilities in Pool. Despite of the peace accords, many Ninja militiamen remained active, and engaged in robberies of civilians and train hijackings.<ref name=\"peace\"/> As of 2009, active Ninja remnants still exist in the southern Pool.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/country_profiles/1076794.stm |title=Country profile: Republic of Congo |date=2009-08-01 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=2010-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091231042330/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/country_profiles/1076794.stm |archive-date=2009-12-31 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2007, Ntoumi announced that the Ninjas were \"going into constructive opposition\" and were determined \"to work for peace in Pool and across the country\". Ninja members led by Ntoumi burned around 100 of their weapons in a ceremony in [[Kinkala]].<ref name=\"peace\"/> On June 10, 2008, the National Programme of Demobilisation, Disarmament and Reintegration (NPDDR), aiming to reintegrate ex-combatants from the wars of the 1990s and 2000s into civilian society, was launched. Ntoumi spoke at the launching in Kinkala and announced the disbanding of the Ninjas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportID=78670 |title=CONGO: DDR gets under way for 30,000 ex-combatants |date=2008-06-10 |publisher=[[IRIN]] News |accessdate=2010-11-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100827170828/http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=78670 |archive-date=2010-08-27 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was offered a government post in September 2007, but remained in hiding until December 2009, when he went to Brazzaville to take up the post.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=87591 |title=In Brief: Former Congolese rebel chief takes up government post |date=2009-12-29 |publisher=[[IRIN]] News |accessdate=2010-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100217100331/http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=87591 |archive-date=2010-02-17 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBernard Kol\u00e9las died in [[Paris]] in 2009.<ref name=\"kolelas\"/>\n\n=== 2010s : Pool war ===\n[[File:Fusils remis par les combattants Ninja au Congo-Brazzaville, 2018.jpg|thumb|Rifles handed over by the Ninjas in 2019.]]\n{{main|Pool War}}\nIn 2016, Bintsamou again raised his forces after contested modifications of the constitution by president Sassou-Nguesso.<ref name=\"Paris1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.parismatch.com/Actu/International/Congo-Brazzaville-N-allez-pas-ramassez-ces-corps-1068667|title=Congo-Brazzaville : \"Ne ramassez pas les corps !\"|date=15 September 2016|publisher=Paris Match|language=fr}}</ref>\nOn 4 April 2016, the Congolese government accused the Ninja militia of attacking security forces. The militia denied the accusations, calling them false pretext for political suppression.<ref name=\"Paris1\" /> Violence continued with events such as shelling by the Congolese armed forces and attacks on trains by the Ninja militia.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ngoussou |first1=Ngouela |title=Des incidents dans le Pool emp\u00eachent le bon fonctionnement du CFCO au Congo |url=https://www.voaafrique.com/a/des-incidents-dans-le-pool-empechent-le-bon-fonctionnement-du-cfco-au-congo/3716350.html |accessdate=15 August 2018 |work=VOA Africa |date=9 February 2017 |language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.parismatch.com/Actu/International/Congo-Brazzaville-Sassou-Nguesso-pompier-pyromane-1093963|title=Congo-Brazzaville: la partie de chasse de Sassou Nguesso|date=13 October 2016|publisher=Paris Match|language=fr}}</ref> The Congolese government and the Ninja militia signed a ceasefire agreement on 23 December 2017. Pursuant to the terms of the agreement, the Ninjas were to hand over their arms and cease their interference with trade between the cities of Brazzaville and Pointe Noire.<ref name=\"ceasefire\">{{cite news |last1=McAllister |first1=Edward |last2=Elion |first2=Christian |last3=Powell |first3=Stephen |title=Congo Republic signs peace accord with |url=https://af.reuters.com/article/africaTech/idAFKBN1EI07E-OZATP |accessdate=15 August 2018 |work=Reuters Africa |date=24 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Human rights violations ==\nAccording to a 2000 report by [[USCIS]] there were \"numerous credible reports of grave human-rights violations committed by ''Ninja'' militia forces ... including [[hostage-taking]], [[torture]] and [[extrajudicial executions]].\" An [[Amnesty International]] report cited by USCIS stated that \"[f]rom June 1997, ''Ninja'' and ''Cocoye'' combatants reportedly killed hundreds and possibly thousands of unarmed civilians at roadblocks in their Bacongo and Mak\u00e9l\u00e9k\u00e9l\u00e9 strongholds.\"<ref name=\"USCIS\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Foreign ninja]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Guerrilla organizations]]\n[[Category:Rebel groups in the Republic of the Congo]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox War Faction\n|name = Ninjas\n|war = the [[Pool War]]\n|image =File:Des ex- rebelles Ninjas \u00e0 Kinkala, Congo-Brazzaville, le 20 juin 2019.jpg\n|caption = Former Ninja fighters in 2019\n|active =Early 1990s\u20132008; 2016\u20132017\n|leaders = [[Bernard Kol\u00e9las]]<br>[[Frederick Bintsamou|Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bintsangou]] a.k.a. Pastor Ntoumi\n|clans =\n|ideology =\n|headquarters = [[Brazzaville]] (until 1997)<br>[[Pool Department]]\n|area = [[Republic of the Congo]]\n|strength = Estimates of some hundred active; up to 3,000 loosely attached fighters as of 2002<ref name=\"civilians\"/>\n|previous =\n|next =\n|allies = 1993\u201394 conflict: Cobra militia<br>1997\u201399 Civil War: Cocoye militia<br> [[Republic of the Congo]] (1997)\n|opponents = {{flag|Republic of the Congo}}<br> Cocoye militia (1993\u201394)<br> Cobra militia (from 1997)<br> {{flag|Angola}} (1997)<ref name=\"USCIS\"/>\n|battles= \n* [[Republic of the Congo Civil War (1993\u201394)]]\n* [[Republic of the Congo Civil War (1997-99)|Republic of the Congo Civil War]] (1997\u201399)\n* [[2002\u201303 conflict in the Pool Department]]\n* [[Pool War]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Ninjas''' were a [[militia]] in the [[Republic of the Congo]], which participated in numerous wars and insurgencies in the 1990s and 2000s. The Ninjas were formed by the politician [[Bernard Kol\u00e9las]] in the early 1990s and were commanded by [[Frederick Bintsamou|Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bintsamou]], alias Pastor Ntoumi when Kolelas was in exile.\n\nThe militia fought the supporters of President [[Pascal Lissouba]] in the 1993\u201394 armed conflict in the Congo. In the 1997\u201399 [[Republic of the Congo Civil War (1997-99)|Republic of the Congo Civil War]], they allied with Lissouba's forces against the supporters of former President [[Denis Sassou Nguesso]]. After Sassou Nguesso's victory in the Civil War, Ntoumi's Ninjas fought an insurgency against his government in the [[Pool Department]]. The conflict in the Pool escalated in a series of violent clashes in 2002-03, after which the Ninja leadership eventually gave up their armed struggle. Ntoumi announced the disbanding of the Ninjas in 2008 but they resurfaced in 2016, starting the [[Pool War]].\n\n==Character and ideology==\n[[Image:Pastor Ntumi in 2007.jpg|thumb|left|Frederick Bintsamou who is also known as Pastor Ntoumi.]]\nFormed by and originally loyal to [[Bernard Kol\u00e9las]],<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=57515 |title=CONGO: Profile of ex-Prime Minister Bernard Kolelas |date=2005-12-09 |publisher=[[IRIN]] News |accessdate=2010-01-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611170737/http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=57515 |archive-date=2011-06-11 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"kolelas\">{{cite news |title=Congo Ninja leader dies, aged 76 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8359087.stm |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=2009-11-13 |accessdate=2010-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091116145018/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8359087.stm |archive-date=2009-11-16 |url-status=live }}</ref> the Ninja militia was associated with the [[Bakongo]] ethnic group.<ref name=\"civilians\">{{cite web |url=http://www.irinnews.org/report.aspx?reportid=32237 |title=CONGO: Civilians bear brunt of attacks on \"Ninja\" rebels |date=2003-06-03 |publisher=[[IRIN]] News |accessdate=2010-01-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100219011750/http://www.irinnews.org/report.aspx?reportid=32237 |archive-date=2010-02-19 |url-status=live }}</ref> The militia was named after the [[ninja]]s of feudal Japan.<ref name=\"peace\">{{cite news |title=Congo's Ninja rebels burn weapons and pledge peace |first=Christian |last=Tsoumou |url=http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L08473674.htm |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=2007-06-08 |accessdate=2010-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090804102134/http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L08473674.htm |archive-date=2009-08-04 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Ninja field commander, [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bintsamou|Pastor Ntoumi]], has been described as a cult leader<ref name=\"civilians\"/> and a \"messianic pastor\". In 2003, he told a journalist that the [[Holy Spirit]] told him to revive the Ninjas. Ninja militiamen wore the colour purple (symbolizing suffering), and had their hair in dreadlocks. They were reported to believe that the [[apocalypse]] was near.<ref>{{cite news|title=Apocalyptic rebel movement revisits Congo's heart of darkness|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2003/dec/07/congo.rorycarroll|first=Rory|last=Carroll|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=2003-12-07|accessdate=2010-01-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130827192004/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2003/dec/07/congo.rorycarroll|archive-date=2013-08-27|url-status=live}}</ref>  A Ninja leader quoted in a 2000 report claimed that there were \"almost 16,000 ''Ninjas'' in the Pool region\".<ref name=\"USCIS\">{{cite web |url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/country,,USCIS,,COG,456d621e2,3dedffab4,0.html |title=Republic of Congo (Brazzaville): Information on the human rights situation and the Ninja militia |author=[[USCIS|United States Bureau of Citizenship and Immigration Services]] |date=2000-11-14 |accessdate=2010-01-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010075537/http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/country,,USCIS,,COG,456d621e2,3dedffab4,0.html |archivedate=2012-10-10 }}</ref> According to a 2002 news report by [[IRIN]] News, analysts believed Ntoumi commanded \"only a few hundred dedicated fighters and up to 3,000 more loosely attached\", the latter of which were divided and unenthusiastic.<ref name=\"civilians\"/>\n\n== History ==\n=== 1990s: Foundation and Civil War ===\nThe Republic of the Congo, formerly the [[People's Republic of the Congo]] (1970\u20131991), abolished its [[Marxism-Leninism|Marxist-Leninist]] [[one-party state|one-party system]] in 1991. In the new multi-party state, rivaling political leaders formed their own [[militia]]s.<ref name=\"Pennsylvania\"/> [[Denis Sassou Nguesso]], President for much of the one-party era, formed the Cobra militia. [[Pascal Lissouba]], elected President from 1992, formed the Ministerial Guard, or Cocoye militia, and the Zulu militia.<ref name=\"AfricanAffairs\"/> Bernard Kol\u00e9las, leader of the [[Mouvement Congolais pour la D\u00e9mocratie et la D\u00e9veloppement Integral]] (MCDDI) party, formed the Ninjas, recruiting from his party.<ref name=\"profile\"/> After the disputed [[Republic of the Congo parliamentary election, 1993|1993 elections]], violent conflict between the militias began. In this conflict, which lasted until 1994, the Ninjas were allied with Sassou Nguesso's Cobras against Lissouba's Cocoyes.<ref name=\"USCIS\"/> In December 1995, the parties in the conflict signed a peace treaty where they agreed that militiamen aged 18\u201324 would be integrated into the national [[gendarmerie]] and police force.<ref name=\"AfricanAffairs\"/> [[UNESCO]] also launched a plan to disarm the militias.<ref name=\"Pennsylvania\"/> These programs to pacify the country were controversial and unsuccessful, and the militias survived.<ref name=\"Pennsylvania\"/><ref name=\"AfricanAffairs\"/> In peacetime, the morale among the Ninjas suffered due to lack of payments.<ref name=\"AfricanAffairs\"/>\n\nThe [[Republic of the Congo Civil War (1997-99)|Republic of the Congo Civil War]] began in June 1997, when the supporters of President Lissouba (including the [[Military of the Republic of the Congo|Army]] and the Cocoye, Zulu, and Mamba militias) clashed with those of Denis Sassou Nguesso (including the Cobra militia and Sassou Nguesso's sympathizers in the army). Kol\u00e9las, then Mayor of [[Brazzaville]], was initially neutral. The Ninja-controlled districts of Brazzaville, Bacongo and Mak\u00e9l\u00e9k\u00e9l\u00e9 therefore suffered far less casualties than the rest of the city during the first months of the war. In September, Kol\u00e9las sided with Lissouba, and was installed as Prime Minister. The Ninjas thus entered the war on Lissouba's side.<ref name=\"AfricanAffairs\">{{cite journal |last=Bazenguissa-Ganga |first=R\u00e9my |date=January 1999 |title=The Spread of Political Violence in Congo-Brazzaville |journal=[[African Affairs]] |volume=98 |issue=390 |pages=37\u201354 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |jstor=723683 |doi=10.1093/oxfordjournals.afraf.a008001}}</ref> The alliance between the Ninjas and Lissouba's Cocoyes was formalized with the founding of the Mouvement National pour la Liberation du Congo (MNLC),<ref name=\"Pennsylvania\">{{cite web |url=http://www.africa.upenn.edu/Hornet/irin_21799.html |title=CONGO-BRAZZAVILLE: Background on militia groups |first=Ali B. |last=Ali-Dinar |date=1999-02-17 |publisher=[[University of Pennsylvania]]: African Studies Center |accessdate=2010-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628231107/http://www.africa.upenn.edu/Hornet/irin_21799.html |archive-date=2010-06-28 |url-status=live }}</ref> but Ninja leaders such as [[Claude-Ernest Ndalla]] and [[Willy Matsanga]] opposed the alliance and defected with their men to Sassou Nguesso's side.<ref name=\"AfricanAffairs\"/>\n\nSassou Nguesso's forces, supported by [[Angola]], took control of Brazzaville in October 1997, and overthrew Lissouba's government. Sassou Nguesso returned to the presidency.<ref name=\"AfricanAffairs\"/> The Ninjas retreated to the [[Pool Department]] and fought an insurgency against the new government.<ref name=\"Pennsylvania\"/> In 1999, leaders of the Ninjas and Cocoyes signed a ceasefire agreement. Following the ceasefire and defeats against government forces, about 2000 Ninjas and Cocoyes surrendered to the government. The ceasefire agreement was condemned by Kol\u00e9las. By 1999, American sources speculated if Kol\u00e9las and Lissouba were no longer in control of their militias.<ref name=\"USCIS\"/>\n\n=== 2000s: Pool insurgency ===\n[[Image:Pool districts.png|thumb|right|250px|Map showing districts of Pool as well as Pool's location within the Republic of the Congo.]]\nThere were several major clashes between government forces and Ninjas in 2002 and 2003,<ref name=\"timeline\">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/country_profiles/1076836.stm |title=Timeline: Republic of Congo |date=2009-08-01 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=2010-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926162538/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/country_profiles/1076836.stm |archive-date=2009-09-26 |url-status=live }}</ref> resulting in large humanitarian casualties.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=45904 |title=CONGO: UN warns of \"acute humanitarian crisis\" in Pool region |date=2003-09-03 |publisher=[[IRIN]] News |accessdate=2010-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611170706/http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=45904 |archive-date=2011-06-11 |url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2003, Ninja leaders signed agreements with the government to cease hostilities in Pool. Despite of the peace accords, many Ninja militiamen remained active, and engaged in robberies of civilians and train hijackings.<ref name=\"peace\"/> As of 2009, active Ninja remnants still exist in the southern Pool.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/country_profiles/1076794.stm |title=Country profile: Republic of Congo |date=2009-08-01 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=2010-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091231042330/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/country_profiles/1076794.stm |archive-date=2009-12-31 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2007, Ntoumi announced that the Ninjas were \"going into constructive opposition\" and were determined \"to work for peace in Pool and across the country\". Ninja members led by Ntoumi burned around 100 of their weapons in a ceremony in [[Kinkala]].<ref name=\"peace\"/> On June 10, 2008, the National Programme of Demobilisation, Disarmament and Reintegration (NPDDR), aiming to reintegrate ex-combatants from the wars of the 1990s and 2000s into civilian society, was launched. Ntoumi spoke at the launching in Kinkala and announced the disbanding of the Ninjas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportID=78670 |title=CONGO: DDR gets under way for 30,000 ex-combatants |date=2008-06-10 |publisher=[[IRIN]] News |accessdate=2010-11-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100827170828/http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=78670 |archive-date=2010-08-27 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was offered a government post in September 2007, but remained in hiding until December 2009, when he went to Brazzaville to take up the post.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=87591 |title=In Brief: Former Congolese rebel chief takes up government post |date=2009-12-29 |publisher=[[IRIN]] News |accessdate=2010-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100217100331/http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=87591 |archive-date=2010-02-17 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBernard Kol\u00e9las died in [[Paris]] in 2009.<ref name=\"kolelas\"/>\n\n=== 2010s : Pool war ===\n[[File:Fusils remis par les combattants Ninja au Congo-Brazzaville, 2018.jpg|thumb|Rifles handed over by the Ninjas in 2019.]]\n{{main|Pool War}}\nIn 2016, Bintsamou again raised his forces after contested modifications of the constitution by president Sassou-Nguesso.<ref name=\"Paris1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.parismatch.com/Actu/International/Congo-Brazzaville-N-allez-pas-ramassez-ces-corps-1068667|title=Congo-Brazzaville : \"Ne ramassez pas les corps !\"|date=15 September 2016|publisher=Paris Match|language=fr}}</ref>\nOn 4 April 2016, the Congolese government accused the Ninja militia of attacking security forces. The militia denied the accusations, calling them false pretext for political suppression.<ref name=\"Paris1\" /> Violence continued with events such as shelling by the Congolese armed forces and attacks on trains by the Ninja militia.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ngoussou |first1=Ngouela |title=Des incidents dans le Pool emp\u00eachent le bon fonctionnement du CFCO au Congo |url=https://www.voaafrique.com/a/des-incidents-dans-le-pool-empechent-le-bon-fonctionnement-du-cfco-au-congo/3716350.html |accessdate=15 August 2018 |work=VOA Africa |date=9 February 2017 |language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.parismatch.com/Actu/International/Congo-Brazzaville-Sassou-Nguesso-pompier-pyromane-1093963|title=Congo-Brazzaville: la partie de chasse de Sassou Nguesso|date=13 October 2016|publisher=Paris Match|language=fr}}</ref> The Congolese government and the Ninja militia signed a ceasefire agreement on 23 December 2017. Pursuant to the terms of the agreement, the Ninjas were to hand over their arms and cease their interference with trade between the cities of Brazzaville and Pointe Noire.<ref name=\"ceasefire\">{{cite news |last1=McAllister |first1=Edward |last2=Elion |first2=Christian |last3=Powell |first3=Stephen |title=Congo Republic signs peace accord with |url=https://af.reuters.com/article/africaTech/idAFKBN1EI07E-OZATP |accessdate=15 August 2018 |work=Reuters Africa |date=24 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Human rights violations ==\nAccording to a 2000 report by [[USCIS]] there were \"numerous credible reports of grave human-rights violations committed by ''Ninja'' militia forces ... including [[hostage-taking]], [[torture]] and [[extrajudicial executions]].\" An [[Amnesty International]] report cited by USCIS stated that \"[f]rom June 1997, ''Ninja'' and ''Cocoye'' combatants reportedly killed hundreds and possibly thousands of unarmed civilians at roadblocks in their Bacongo and Mak\u00e9l\u00e9k\u00e9l\u00e9 strongholds.\"<ref name=\"USCIS\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Foreign ninja]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Guerrilla organizations]]\n[[Category:Rebel groups in the Republic of the Congo]]\n", "name_user": "Darthkenobi0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ninja_(militia)"}
{"title_page": "Adelaide Herrmann", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Adelaide Herrmann\n| image              = File:Adelaide Herrmann, head-and-shoulders portrait, facing right LCCN94500214.jpg\n| caption            = Herrmann as Sleeping Beauty\n| birth_name         = Adelaide Scarcez (Scarsia)\n| birth_date         = 1853\n| birth_place        = London, England\n| death_date         = {{Death date|1932|02|19}}\n| death_place        = New York, NY\n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = \n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n'''Adelaide Herrmann''' (1853&ndash;1932) was a well-known American [[magic (illusion)|magician]] and vaudeville performer billed as \"the Queen of Magic.\"<ref name=\"obit\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1932/02/20/archives/mme-hermann-79-illusionist-is-dead-widow-of-magician-appeared-on.html|title=Mme. Hermann, 79, Illusionist, is Dead [full article requires paid access]|last=|first=|date=20 Feb 1932|work=New York Times|accessdate=7 March 2017|page=15}}</ref> She was married to [[Alexander Herrmann]], another magician.\n[[File:Harvard Theatre Collection - Hermann TCS 28.jpg|thumb|Adelaide Herrmann performing|alt=]]\n\n==Early Career==\nAdelaide Herrmann was born Adelaide Scarcez (also spelled Scarsia) in 1853 in London. Her father, who was born in Belgium, helped establish the [[Egyptian Hall]].<ref name=\"obit\"/>\n\nAs a young woman, she studied aerial acrobatics and dance. She learned to ride the [[velocipede]], a 19th-century bicycle, and traveled as a trick-rider with Professor Brown\u2019s velocipede troupe.<ref name=Meier2018>{{cite news|url=https://narratively.com/she-caught-bullets-with-her-bare-hands-and-made-magics-glass-ceiling-disappear/|title=She Caught Bullets with Her Bare Hands \u2014 and Made Magic\u2019s Glass Ceiling Disappear |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> In 1874 she came to New York City as a dancer for [[The Kiralfy Brothers|Imre Kiralfy]].<ref name=\"obit\"/> \n\nShe began her magic career as assistant to her husband, magician [[Alexander Herrmann]]. They married in 1875 at City Hall, where New York City Mayor [[William H. Wickham]] performed their ceremony.<ref name=\"obit\"/> Together, Alexander (\"Professor Herrmann\" or \"Herrmann the Great\") and Adelaide entertained audiences with a variety of magic tricks, including [[escapology|escape tricks]] and the [[bullet catch]] trick. Adelaide was a key part of many illusions, performing as a levitating sleeper, a human cannonball, a bicycle rider who carried a girl on her shoulders, and a dancer who spectrally swirled in red silk like a pillar of fire.<ref name=\"Meier2018\" /> The Herrmanns toured the United States, Mexico, South America, and Europe. \n\nIn 1888, the Herrmanns put on a show wherein they revealed how the spiritualist [[Ann O'Delia Diss Debar]] was a fraudulent medium in front of journalists.''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1888/05/28/archives/making-spirit-pictures-herrmanns-way-of-doing-the-diss-debar.html|title=Making Spirit Pictures: Herrmann's way of doing the Diss Debar Performance. [full article requires paid access]|last=|first=|date=28 May 1888|work=New York Times|accessdate=7 March 2017|page=5}}</ref>''\n\n==Solo Career==\nWhen Alexander died in 1896, Adelaide Herrmann decided to continued the show.<ref name=\"dawes\">{{Cite journal|last = Dawes|first = Edwin A|title = The Great Illusionists|publisher = Chartwell Books (New Jersey)|year = 1979|isbn = 0-89009-240-0|postscript = <!--None-->|url-access = registration|url = https://archive.org/details/greatillusionist00dawe}}</ref><ref name=\"steele\">{{cite web|url = http://www.amazingmagicshow.com/Addie.htm|title = Adelaide, Queen of Magic|publisher = Margaret Steele|accessdate = 2007-04-12}}</ref> She initially worked with her husband's nephew, Leon Herrmann, but a [[clash of personalities]] led them to part ways after only three seasons.<ref name=\"Meier2018\" />\n\nAfterwards, Adelaide Herrmann became extremely well-known as a magician in her own right, earning the moniker \"The Queen of Magic.\"<ref name=\"obit\"/> She toured as a headliner for over 25 years and performed internationally, touring London and Paris.<ref>{{cite news|title=Theatrical Gossip [full article requires paid access]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1898/07/23/archives/germans-grow-fond-of-americans.html|accessdate=7 March 2017|work=New York Times|date=23 July 1898}}</ref> In 1903, she made her [[Broadway theater|Broadway]] debut at the Circle Theater.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1903/05/31/archives/theatres-are-made-ready-for-expected-hot-spell-punch-judy-co-will.html|title=Theaters are made ready for expected Hot Spell [full article requires paid access]|last=|first=|date=31 May 1903|work=New York Times|accessdate=7 March 2017|page=11}}</ref> She performed often with other vaudeville acts and was frequently mentioned in the ''New York Times.'' In a November 2, 1899 article for Broadway Magazine entitled \u201cThe World\u2019s Only Woman Magician,\u201d Herrmann stated, \u201cI shall not be content until I am recognized by the public as a leader in my profession, and entirely irrespective of the question of sex.\u201d<ref name=\"Meier2018\" />\n\nHerrmann was one of the few magicians to perform the infamous \"[[bullet catch]]\" trick, and possibly the only woman magician to perform the trick at the time.<ref name=\"obit\"/> Despite reports that she had disliked watching her husband perform the dangerous trick, on January 19, 1897, a month after his death, she stood in his place in front of a firing squad at the Metropolitan Opera House in Chicago. Surviving publicity material describes her as catching six bullets fired at her by local militiamen.<ref name=\"dawes\"/> \n\nHer favorite illusion was \u201cThe Phantom Bride,\u201d which had themes of loss and marriage. Through \u201chypnotism,\u201d she made a bride\u2019s body, draped in white, rise on a brightly lit stage. She passed a hoop over her hovering form, showing there were no wires, then pulled away the white silk \u2014 the bride was gone. In \u201cThe Witch\u201d illusion, she stumbled onto the stage dressed as an old woman, trying to reach a fire burning in the darkness. When she finally arrived at the pyre, she dove into the flames. Unlike her older \u201cCremation\u201d act, where she returned as a taunting ghost, she now emerged reborn and youthful.<ref name=\"Meier2018\" />\n\nHer \u201cNoah\u2019s Ark\u201d was her greatest vaudevillian hit. At first an ark was shown empty, then buckets of water symbolizing the flood were poured down its chimney. Soon two cats, one black and one white, climbed from the chimney, while a gangplank emerged over which prowled a parade of dogs in costumes of birds, leopards, lions, tigers, zebras, and elephants. A flock of white doves flew from the windows, and the biblical boat opened to reveal a lounging woman dressed in white.<ref name=\"Meier2018\" />\n\nHerrmann continued performing into her 70s until 1926, when a deadly warehouse fire at a theatrical warehouse on West 46th Street in Manhattan destroyed her props and killed most of the animals used in the \"Noah's Ark\" illusion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1926/09/08/archives/fire-kills-one-man-200-stage-animals-owner-of-trained-kangaroos.html|title=Fire kills one man, 200 Stage Animals [full article requires paid access]|last=|first=|date=8 Sep 1926|work=New York Times|accessdate=7 March 2017}}</ref> She rebounded briefly with a pared-down show called \u201cMagic, Grace and Music,\u201d highlighting the three elements at which she\u2019d excelled in her career. The National Vaudeville Artists\u2019 Year Book from 1928 shows Herrmann in her final performing year.<ref name=\"Meier2018\" />\n\nHerrmann died of pneumonia on February 19, 1932.  She is buried at the [[Woodlawn Cemetery, Bronx|Woodlawn Cemetery, New York]].<ref name=\"dawes\"/><ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.thewoodlawncemetery.org/entertainers.html|title=History: Great entertainers|publisher=Woodlawn Cemetery|accessdate=2007-04-12 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311191425/http://www.thewoodlawncemetery.org/entertainers.html|archivedate=11 March 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==Further reading==\n* Margaret Steele (Editor), ''Adelaide Herrmann, Queen of Magic - Memoirs, Published Writings and Collected Ephemera'', Bramble Books (January 2012), {{ISBN|1-883647-19-3}}\n* [[Mary Schendlinger]], ''Prepare to Be Amazed: The Geniuses of Modern Magic'', Annick Press (September  2005), {{ISBN|1-55037-927-5}}\n* [[Mara Rockliff]], ''Anything But Ordinary Addie: The True Story of Adelaide Herrmann Queen of Magic'', illus. by Iacopo Bruno, Candlewick Press (2016), {{ISBN|978-0-7636-6841-9}}\n\n==External links ==\n* [https://www.whatshernamepodcast.com/adelaide-herrmann What'sHerName Podcast, \"THE DISAPPEARING WOMAN Adelaide Herrmann,\" with guest expert [[Paul W. Draper]]]\n* [http://narrative.ly/she-caught-bullets-with-her-bare-hands-and-made-magics-glass-ceiling-disappear/ She caught bullets with her bare hands and made magic's glass ceiling disappear - Adelaide Herrmann Biography]\n{{Magic and Illusion}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Herrmann, Adelaide}}\n[[Category:Burials at Woodlawn Cemetery (Bronx)]]\n[[Category:1853 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:Female magicians]]\n[[Category:American magicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Adelaide Herrmann\n| image              = File:Adelaide Herrmann, head-and-shoulders portrait, facing right LCCN94500214.jpg\n| caption            = Herrmann as Sleeping Beauty\n| birth_name         = Adelaide Scarcez (Scarsia)\n| birth_date         = 1853\n| birth_place        = London, England\n| death_date         = {{Death date|1932|02|19}}\n| death_place        = New York, NY\n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = \n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n'''Adelaide Herrmann''' (1853&ndash;1932) was a well-known American [[magic (illusion)|magician]] and vaudeville performer billed as \"the Queen of Magic.\"<ref name=\"obit\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1932/02/20/archives/mme-hermann-79-illusionist-is-dead-widow-of-magician-appeared-on.html|title=Mme. Hermann, 79, Illusionist, is Dead [full article requires paid access]|last=|first=|date=20 Feb 1932|work=New York Times|accessdate=7 March 2017|page=15}}</ref> She was married to [[Alexander Herrmann]], another magician.\n[[File:Harvard Theatre Collection - Hermann TCS 28.jpg|thumb|Adelaide Herrmann performing|alt=]]\n\n==Early Career==\nAdelaide Herrmann was born Adelaide Scarcez (also spelled Scarsia) in 1853 in London. Her father, who was born in Belgium, helped establish the [[Egyptian Hall]].<ref name=\"obit\"/>\n\nAs a young woman, she studied aerial acrobatics and dance. She learned to ride the velocipede, a 19th-century bicycle, and traveled as a trick-rider with Professor Brown\u2019s velocipede troupe.<ref name=Meier2018>{{cite news|url=https://narratively.com/she-caught-bullets-with-her-bare-hands-and-made-magics-glass-ceiling-disappear/|title=She Caught Bullets with Her Bare Hands \u2014 and Made Magic\u2019s Glass Ceiling Disappear |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> In 1874 she came to New York City as a dancer for [[The Kiralfy Brothers|Imre Kiralfy]].<ref name=\"obit\"/> \n\nShe began her magic career as assistant to her husband, magician [[Alexander Herrmann]]. They married in 1875 at City Hall, where New York City Mayor [[William H. Wickham]] performed their ceremony.<ref name=\"obit\"/> Together, Alexander (\"Professor Herrmann\" or \"Herrmann the Great\") and Adelaide entertained audiences with a variety of magic tricks, including [[escapology|escape tricks]] and the [[bullet catch]] trick. Adelaide was a key part of many illusions, performing as a levitating sleeper, a human cannonball, a bicycle rider who carried a girl on her shoulders, and a dancer who spectrally swirled in red silk like a pillar of fire.<ref name=\"Meier2018\" /> The Herrmanns toured the United States, Mexico, South America, and Europe. \n\nIn 1888, the Herrmanns put on a show wherein they revealed how the spiritualist [[Ann O'Delia Diss Debar]] was a fraudulent medium in front of journalists.''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1888/05/28/archives/making-spirit-pictures-herrmanns-way-of-doing-the-diss-debar.html|title=Making Spirit Pictures: Herrmann's way of doing the Diss Debar Performance. [full article requires paid access]|last=|first=|date=28 May 1888|work=New York Times|accessdate=7 March 2017|page=5}}</ref>''\n\n==Solo Career==\nWhen Alexander died in 1896, Adelaide Herrmann decided to continued the show.<ref name=\"dawes\">{{Cite journal|last = Dawes|first = Edwin A|title = The Great Illusionists|publisher = Chartwell Books (New Jersey)|year = 1979|isbn = 0-89009-240-0|postscript = <!--None-->|url-access = registration|url = https://archive.org/details/greatillusionist00dawe}}</ref><ref name=\"steele\">{{cite web|url = http://www.amazingmagicshow.com/Addie.htm|title = Adelaide, Queen of Magic|publisher = Margaret Steele|accessdate = 2007-04-12}}</ref> She initially worked with her husband's nephew, Leon Herrmann, but a [[clash of personalities]] led them to part ways after only three seasons.<ref name=\"Meier2018\" />\n\nAfterwards, Adelaide Herrmann became extremely well-known as a magician in her own right, earning the moniker \"The Queen of Magic.\"<ref name=\"obit\"/> She toured as a headliner for over 25 years and performed internationally, touring London and Paris.<ref>{{cite news|title=Theatrical Gossip [full article requires paid access]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1898/07/23/archives/germans-grow-fond-of-americans.html|accessdate=7 March 2017|work=New York Times|date=23 July 1898}}</ref> In 1903, she made her [[Broadway theater|Broadway]] debut at the Circle Theater.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1903/05/31/archives/theatres-are-made-ready-for-expected-hot-spell-punch-judy-co-will.html|title=Theaters are made ready for expected Hot Spell [full article requires paid access]|last=|first=|date=31 May 1903|work=New York Times|accessdate=7 March 2017|page=11}}</ref> She performed often with other vaudeville acts and was frequently mentioned in the ''New York Times.'' In a November 2, 1899 article for Broadway Magazine entitled \u201cThe World\u2019s Only Woman Magician,\u201d Herrmann stated, \u201cI shall not be content until I am recognized by the public as a leader in my profession, and entirely irrespective of the question of sex.\u201d<ref name=\"Meier2018\" />\n\nHerrmann was one of the few magicians to perform the infamous \"[[bullet catch]]\" trick, and possibly the only woman magician to perform the trick at the time.<ref name=\"obit\"/> Despite reports that she had disliked watching her husband perform the dangerous trick, on January 19, 1897, a month after his death, she stood in his place in front of a firing squad at the Metropolitan Opera House in Chicago. Surviving publicity material describes her as catching six bullets fired at her by local militiamen.<ref name=\"dawes\"/> \n\nHer favorite illusion was \u201cThe Phantom Bride,\u201d which had themes of loss and marriage. Through \u201chypnotism,\u201d she made a bride\u2019s body, draped in white, rise on a brightly lit stage. She passed a hoop over her hovering form, showing there were no wires, then pulled away the white silk \u2014 the bride was gone. In \u201cThe Witch\u201d illusion, she stumbled onto the stage dressed as an old woman, trying to reach a fire burning in the darkness. When she finally arrived at the pyre, she dove into the flames. Unlike her older \u201cCremation\u201d act, where she returned as a taunting ghost, she now emerged reborn and youthful.<ref name=\"Meier2018\" />\n\nHer \u201cNoah\u2019s Ark\u201d was her greatest vaudevillian hit. At first an ark was shown empty, then buckets of water symbolizing the flood were poured down its chimney. Soon two cats, one black and one white, climbed from the chimney, while a gangplank emerged over which prowled a parade of dogs in costumes of birds, leopards, lions, tigers, zebras, and elephants. A flock of white doves flew from the windows, and the biblical boat opened to reveal a lounging woman dressed in white.<ref name=\"Meier2018\" />\n\nHerrmann continued performing into her 70s until 1926, when a deadly warehouse fire at a theatrical warehouse on West 46th Street in Manhattan destroyed her props and killed most of the animals used in the \"Noah's Ark\" illusion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1926/09/08/archives/fire-kills-one-man-200-stage-animals-owner-of-trained-kangaroos.html|title=Fire kills one man, 200 Stage Animals [full article requires paid access]|last=|first=|date=8 Sep 1926|work=New York Times|accessdate=7 March 2017}}</ref> She rebounded briefly with a pared-down show called \u201cMagic, Grace and Music,\u201d highlighting the three elements at which she\u2019d excelled in her career. The National Vaudeville Artists\u2019 Year Book from 1928 shows Herrmann in her final performing year.<ref name=\"Meier2018\" />\n\nHerrmann died of pneumonia on February 19, 1932.  She is buried at the [[Woodlawn Cemetery, Bronx|Woodlawn Cemetery, New York]].<ref name=\"dawes\"/><ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.thewoodlawncemetery.org/entertainers.html|title=History: Great entertainers|publisher=Woodlawn Cemetery|accessdate=2007-04-12 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311191425/http://www.thewoodlawncemetery.org/entertainers.html|archivedate=11 March 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==Further reading==\n* Margaret Steele (Editor), ''Adelaide Herrmann, Queen of Magic - Memoirs, Published Writings and Collected Ephemera'', Bramble Books (January 2012), {{ISBN|1-883647-19-3}}\n* [[Mary Schendlinger]], ''Prepare to Be Amazed: The Geniuses of Modern Magic'', Annick Press (September  2005), {{ISBN|1-55037-927-5}}\n* [[Mara Rockliff]], ''Anything But Ordinary Addie: The True Story of Adelaide Herrmann Queen of Magic'', illus. by Iacopo Bruno, Candlewick Press (2016), {{ISBN|978-0-7636-6841-9}}\n\n==External links ==\n* [https://www.whatshernamepodcast.com/adelaide-herrmann What'sHerName Podcast, \"THE DISAPPEARING WOMAN Adelaide Herrmann,\" with guest expert [[Paul W. Draper]]]\n* [http://narrative.ly/she-caught-bullets-with-her-bare-hands-and-made-magics-glass-ceiling-disappear/ She caught bullets with her bare hands and made magic's glass ceiling disappear - Adelaide Herrmann Biography]\n{{Magic and Illusion}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Herrmann, Adelaide}}\n[[Category:Burials at Woodlawn Cemetery (Bronx)]]\n[[Category:1853 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:Female magicians]]\n[[Category:American magicians]]\n", "name_user": "Telecineguy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly Career:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adelaide_Herrmann"}
{"title_page": "Mile 22", "text_new": "{{short description|2018 film directed by Peter Berg}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Mile 22\n| image          = Mile 22.png\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Peter Berg]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Peter Berg\n* [[Mark Wahlberg]]\n* Stephen Levinson\n}}\n| screenplay     = [[Lea Carpenter]]\n| story          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Graham Roland]]\n* Lea Carpenter\n}}\n| based on       = \n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* Mark Wahlberg\n* [[Iko Uwais]]\n* [[John Malkovich]]\n* [[Lauren Cohan]]\n* [[Ronda Rousey]]\n* [[Nikolai Nikolaeff]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Jeff Russo]]\n| cinematography = Jacques Jouffret\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* Colby Parker Jr.\n* Melissa Lawson Cheung\n}}\n| studio         = {{ubl|[[STX Entertainment|STXfilms]]|[[Huayi Brothers|H. Brothers]]|The Hideaway Entertainment|[[Donald Tang|Tang Media Productions]]}}\n| distributor    = [[STX Entertainment]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|8|17|United States}}\n| runtime        = 94 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $35\u201360 million<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/mile-22-mark-wahlberg-1202908708/|title=Box Office: Mark Wahlberg\u2019s \u2018Mile 22\u2019 Picks Up $1 Million on Thursday Night|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|first=Brent|last=Lang|date=August 17, 2018|accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=DEADwknd2/>\n| gross          = $66.3 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |title=Mile 22 (2018) |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=mile22.htm |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[IMDb]] |accessdate=November 21, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Mile 22''''' is a 2018 American [[espionage]] [[action film|action]] [[thriller film|thriller]] film directed by [[Peter Berg]] and written by [[Lea Carpenter]], from a story by Carpenter and [[Graham Roland]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shanley|first1=Patrick|title=Mark Wahlberg Action Film 'Mile 22' Gets July Release|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/mark-wahlberg-action-film-mile-22-gets-july-release-1084594|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=February 13, 2018|accessdate=February 25, 2018}}</ref> The film stars [[Mark Wahlberg]], [[Iko Uwais]], [[John Malkovich]], [[Lauren Cohan]], and [[Ronda Rousey]]. It follows an elite CIA task force composed of paramilitary officers from the [[Special Activities Division]]'s Ground Branch, that has to escort a high-priority [[asset (intelligence)|asset]] 22 miles to an extraction point while being hunted by the government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://washingtontimes.com/news/2018/aug/14/peter-berg-asked-mark-wahlberg-to-tap-into-bannon-/|first=Douglas|last=Ernst|date=August 14, 2018|title=Peter Berg asked Mark Wahlberg to tap into \u2018Bannon intensity\u2019 for \u2018Mile 22\u2019|work=[[Washington Times]]|accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.traileraddict.com/mile-22/featurette-ground-branch|title=Mile 22 Featurette - Ground Branch (2018)|date=August 12, 2018 |work=Trailer Addict|accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref> The film marks the fourth collaboration between Berg and Wahlberg, following ''[[Lone Survivor]]'', ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]'', and ''[[Patriots Day (film)|Patriots Day]]''. \n\nThe film was released in the United States on August 17, 2018, and grossed $66 million worldwide. It received generally unfavorable reviews from critics, who called it \"confusing and a chaotic mess,\" alongside criticizing the cinematography and editing in the action sequences, although the performance of Uwais received praise.<!--cited in Reception-->\n\n==Plot==\n[[CIA officer]] and former [[U.S. Marine]] [[Force Recon]] [[veteran]], James Silva, leads a [[Special Activities Center|Special Activities Division]] team code-named Overwatch to raid a Russian [[Federal Security Service|FSB]] safe house in the United States. Under the remote supervision of James Bishop and his team, the mission is to locate and destroy shipments of [[caesium]] before the highly radioactive substance can be weaponized. In the ensuing firefight, most of the Russians and Overwatch operative Greg Vickers are killed, and critical intelligence on the caesium is destroyed. Silva executes the last survivor, a teenager who warns him that he is making a mistake.\n\nSixteen months later, in the [[Southeast Asian]] country of [[List of fictional countries|Indocarr]], police officer Li Noor surrenders himself at the US Embassy to negotiate for passage out of the country in exchange for information. Noor is revealed to be the asset of Overwatch agent Alice Kerr and reveals he possesses a disc containing information on the caesium, and is able to negotiate passage out of the country in exchange for unlocking the disc, which is programmed to self destruct within eight hours. Ambassador Dorothy Brady is visited by the country's Deputy Foreign Minister and state intelligence agent Axel, with the two demanding that Noor be handed over as he is wanted for [[espionage]]. Meanwhile, Noor fends off an assassination attempt by disguised government agents in the embassy infirmary using his skills as a former member of the elite tactical squad. \n\nWanting access to the intel, Silva's team is instructed to take Noor to an airplane at an airstrip 22 miles away, being provided with remote assistance from Bishop's team in [[Colombia]]. En route they are attacked by a group of men on motorcycles, who use a brief camera blackout to plant a bomb on one of the vehicles. During the ensuing gunfight, operative Sam Snow is mortally injured, and sacrifices herself to buy the group time. Taking cover in a restaurant, they are again attacked by Axel's men, in which Silva is saved by Noor and operative William \u201cDougie\u201d Douglas is seriously injured. The group retreats into an apartment complex, and Douglas sacrifices himself by putting down cover fire. Inside the building, Alice becomes separated from Silva and Noor, but is able to escape harm by using grenades and is later saved by Noor. Axel attempts to stop their car from reaching the airstrip, but is killed by Bishop's team via a [[drone strike]]. Arriving just before the plane takes off, Noor and Alice board the aircraft, with Alice having been given time off to see her estranged daughter. Noor provides Overwatch with the passcode to access the disk, with the intel appearing to be legitimate locations of the caesium. \n\nNoticing that the password \"rozhdestvo111\" matches the address of the FSB safehouse at the start of the film which was Christmas 111, Bishop comes to the conclusion Noor has betrayed them, and is actually acting as a [[triple agent]] for the [[Russian government]]. The mission is compromised.  A team [[Beriev A-50]], led by Senior Lieutenant Aleksander Aslanov, breaches the CIA's secure communications and control room. The teenager killed by Silva at the safehouse is shown to be Anatole Kuragin, the son of high ranking government official Vera Kuragina, who ordered the operation and sought personal revenge against the group. She hired Noor to serve as Alice\u2019s informant so they would trust him and activate Overwatch.  The purpose of Noor's unique negotiation has been to reveal the ultimate depths of the CIA special teams.  On the plane, Noor disarms a guard and breaches the cockpit, as revealed by communications from the plane. Alice\u2019s fate is uncertain. The team in Colombia, having been traced by the Russians, are gunned down, with a critically injured Bishop barely escaping. Having been unable to stop what occurred, Silva tells of his experience during a post-mission debriefing. Returning to his apartment, he puts up a picture of Noor on his wall, vowing revenge.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Mark Wahlberg]] as James Silva / \"Child 1\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Check out the first images and poster for Mark Wahlberg's Mile 22|url=http://www.joblo.com/movie-news/check-out-the-first-images-and-poster-for-mark-wahlberg-s-mile-22-135|website=[[JoBlo.com]]|publisher=Joblo Media|date=April 24, 2018|first=Kevin|last=Fraser|accessdate=May 7, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Lauren Cohan]] as Alice Kerr / \"Child 2\"<ref name=\"Cast\">{{cite news|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/mile-22/273474/mile-22-trailer-release-date-cast-story-details-and-set-visit|title=''Mile 22'' Trailer, Release Date, Cast, Story Details, and Set Visit|website=Den of Geek!|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|date=June 28, 2018|accessdate=July 2, 2018|last=Crow|first=David}}</ref>\n* [[Iko Uwais]] as Li Noor<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[John Malkovich]] as James Bishop / \"Mother\"<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[Ronda Rousey]] as Samantha \"Sam\" Snow / \"Child 3\"<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[Nikolai Nikolaeff]] as [[Army ranks and insignia of the Russian Federation|Senior Lieutenant]] Aleksander Aslanov<ref>{{cite web |title=Interview: Actor Nikolai Nikolaeff |url=https://reeltalker.com/2018/05/30/interview-actor-nikolai-nikolaeff/ |website=Reel Talker |date=May 30, 2018 |first=Jim |last=Alexander |accessdate=July 31, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Carlo Alban]] as William \"Dougie\" Douglas III/ \"Child 4\"<ref name=\"slashcast\">{{cite web |last1=Giroux |first1=Jack |title=\u2018Mile 22\u2019 Set Visit: Mark Wahlberg and His Team Get Sh*t Done |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/mile-22-set-visit/ |website=[[/Film]] |date=June 5, 2018 |accessdate=July 31, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Terry Kinney]]<ref name=\"firstcast\">{{cite web |last1=Billington |first1=Alex |title=Official Trailer for Gritty Action Movie 'Mile 22' with Mark Wahlberg |url=http://www.firstshowing.net/2018/official-trailer-for-gritty-action-movie-mile-22-with-mark-wahlberg/ |date=May 15, 2018 |website=FirstShowing.net |accessdate=July 31, 2018}}</ref> as Johnny Porter\n* [[Poorna Jagannathan]]<ref name=\"firstcast\"/> as Ambassador Dorothy Brady\n* Sam Medina as Axel<ref name=\"slashcast\"/>\n* Natasha Goubskaya as Vera Kuragina\n* David Garelik as Anatole Kuragin\n* Alexandra Vino as Sergeant Thomas<ref name=\"firstcast\"/>\n* [[Cedric Gervais]]<ref>{{cite tweet|title=In theaters August 17th #mile22|user=CedricGervais|first=Cedric|last=Gervais|number=1025119374959620096|date=August 2, 2018|accessdate=August 2, 2018}}</ref> as Greg Vickers / \"Child 5\"\n* [[CL (singer)|Chae Rin Lee]] as Queen<ref>{{cite web | url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3048287 | title=CL to play a killer in upcoming film | work=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]] | date=May 18, 2018 | last=Sung |first=Ji-eun | accessdate=August 10, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Emily Skeggs]] as M.I.T.\n* [[Peter Berg]] as Lucas\n* [[Lateef Crowder]] as Liam\n}}\n\n== Production ==\nOn March 2, 2015, it was announced that [[Ronda Rousey]] and [[Iko Uwais]] were set to star in the action-thriller film ''Mile 22'' scripted by [[Graham Roland]], with [[Peter Berg]] attached as producer. WME Global was in talks to finance the film.<ref name=Mar2015Variety>{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Ronda Rousey, Sam Medina, Peter Berg and Iko Uwais Team on Action Pic \u2018Mile 22\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/ronda-rousey-peter-berg-and-iko-uwais-team-on-action-pic-mile-22-exclusive-1201319883/|accessdate=October 27, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=March 2, 2015}}</ref> On July 2, 2015, [[Mark Wahlberg]] was cast in the film to play the male lead role, while Berg was also confirmed to direct the film for [[STX Entertainment]]. Berg would also produce the film along with Wahlberg and Stephen Levinson.<ref name=Jul2015THR>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title=Mark Wahlberg, Peter Berg Teaming Up for STX Action Movie 'Mile 22' (Exclusive)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/mark-wahlberg-peter-berg-teaming-806603|accessdate=October 27, 2015|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=July 2, 2015}}</ref> On March 28, 2017, Wahlberg and Berg announced that they are moving ahead with ''Mile 22'' as a trilogy of films.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Mark Wahlberg, Peter Berg Plan to Make Action Movie \u2018Mile 22\u2019 a Trilogy|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/mark-wahlberg-action-movie-mile-22-stx-1202017981/|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=March 28, 2017|accessdate=February 21, 2018}}</ref> On November 7, 2017, [[Lauren Cohan]] was cast in the film.<ref name=\"CohanCast\">{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title='Walking Dead' Star Lauren Cohan Joins Mark Walhberg in Action Movie 'Mile 22'|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/walking-dead-star-lauren-cohan-joins-mark-walhberg-action-movie-mile-22-1055807|accessdate=November 8, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=November 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Principal photography]] on the film was shot in [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] in November and December 2017 under the working title ''Ground Branch Triple'',<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hensley|first1=Ellie|title=Report: Mark Wahlberg, Ronda Rousey movie to film in Atlanta|url=https://bizjournals.com/atlanta/news/2017/09/21/report-mark-wahlberg-ronda-rousey-movie-to-film.html|newspaper=Atlanta Business Chronicle|publisher=[[American City Business Journals]]|date=September 21, 2017|accessdate=February 21, 2018}}</ref> and in [[Colombia]] in the capital city [[Bogot\u00e1]] and its surroundings in January and February 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mark Wahlberg y John Malkovich est\u00e1n en Bogot\u00e1 para rodar una pel\u00edcula |url=http://www.eltiempo.com/cultura/cine-y-tv/pelicula-de-john-malkovich-y-mark-wahlberg-que-sera-grabada-en-bogota-175480 |trans-title=Mark Wahlberg and John Malkovich are in Bogot\u00e1 to shoot a movie |newspaper=[[El Tiempo (Colombia)|El Tiempo]] |language=es |date=January 29, 2018 |accessdate=February 20, 2018}}</ref> On February 5, 2018, [[President of Colombia|Colombian President]] [[Juan Manuel Santos]] showed up during filming at one of the locations in Colombia. Director Peter Berg even had President Santos try to shoot one of the action sequences of the film.<ref>{{cite news|title=Santos turns up during Bogot\u00e1 shoot of \"Mile 22\" starring Mark Wahlberg|url=https://thecitypaperbogota.com/bogota/santos-turns-up-during-bogota-shoot-of-mile-22-starring-mark-wahlberg/18949|author=The City Paper Staff|newspaper=The City Paper Bogot\u00e1|date=February 5, 2018|accessdate=February 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThe final trailer was released online on July 26, 2018.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Foutch | first1=Haleigh | title=Final \u2018Mile 22\u2019 Trailer Teases Mark Wahlberg & Peter Berg\u2019s Action-Packed Thriller | date=July 26, 2018 | url=http://collider.com/mile-22-trailer/ | website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |publisher=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex Media]] | accessdate=July 31, 2018}}</ref> The film was originally going to be released on August 3, 2018, but was pushed back two weeks to August 17, 2018.\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Mile 22'' grossed $37.6 million in the United States and Canada, and $28.7 million in other territories, for a total worldwide gross of $66.3 million.<ref name=BOM/>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, ''Mile 22'' was released alongside ''[[Alpha (2018 film)|Alpha]]'', and was projected to gross around $17 million from 3,520 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-box-office-opening-fandango-presales-online-buzz-1202445334/|title=\u2018Crazy Rich Asians\u2019 Could Hit $30M In 5-Day Opening; Fandango Presales Currently Besting \u2018Girls Trip\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |date=August 14, 2018 |first=Anthony |last= D'Alessandro |accessdate=August 14, 2018}}</ref> It made $5.3 million on its first day, including $1 million from Thursday night previews at 2,600 theaters. It went on to debut to $13.6 million, finishing third at the box office.<ref name=opening>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-wednesday-opening-box-office-1202446094/|title=\u2018Crazy Rich Asians\u2019 Even Richer On Saturday With $10M+; Weekend Bling Now At $25M+ With $34M 5-Day Debut|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |date=August 19, 2018 |first=Anthony |last= D'Alessandro |accessdate=August 19, 2018}}</ref> In its second weekend the film dropped to sixth place, making $6 million.<ref name=DEADwknd2>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/melissa-mccarthy-happytime-murders-crazy-rich-asians-meg-weekend-box-office-1202451694/|title=\u2018Why \u2018Happytime Murders\u2019 Reps A Solo Career B.O. Low For Melissa McCarthy In A \u2018Crazy Rich\u2019 Weekend \u2013 Update|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |date=August 26, 2018 |first=Anthony |last= D'Alessandro |accessdate=August 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 23% based on 169 reviews, with an average rating of 4.1/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Mile 22'' lets the bullets fly\u2014and not much else\u2014in a thrill-deficient action thriller whose title proves sadly fitting for a film that feels close to a marathon endurance test.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/mile_22/|title=Mile 22 (2018)|publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating to reviews, the film has a weighted average score of 39 out of 100, based on 32 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/mile-22|title=Mile 22 Reviews|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=August 27, 2018}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B\u2212\" on an A+ to F scale, while [[PostTrak]] reported filmgoers gave it a 63% positive score.<ref name=opening/>\n\nThe performance of Uwais received some praise. Katie Walsh of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' said, \"As a performer and fight choreographer, Uwais delivers, with some extremely athletic and imaginative kills, mostly performed while handcuffed. It's also far and away Uwais's best acting performance in a film, and he almost makes ''Mile 22'' worth it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-mile-22-review-20180816-story.html|title=Review: Peter Berg and Mark Wahlberg pack action-thriller \u2018Mile 22\u2019 with maximum overkill|first=Katie|last=Walsh|date=August 16, 2018|accessdate=August 21, 2018|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> Brian Lowry of [[CNN]] stated, \"In fact, Uwais' action sequences\u2014fast paced and electric\u2014are easily the highlight of a movie otherwise characterized by an abundance of automatic-weapons fire and tedious dialogue during the fleeting gaps between those bursts.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/16/entertainment/mile-22-review/index.html|title='Mile 22' loads up brutal action vehicle that misses the mark|first=Brian|last=Lowry|date=August 16, 2018|accessdate=August 21, 2018|work=CNN Entertainment|publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref> David Fear of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the film 2 out of 5 stars, criticizing the editing of the fight scenes and stating, \"Why go through the trouble of giving Iko Uwais several fight scenes and editing them so that you can barely see the star inflict highly choreographed damage?...''Mile 22'' can give you chase scenes and bullet-ridden shoot-outs and evil Russians and lengthy diatribes. It can give you something approximating action. What it can't give you is a watchable action movie. That's where it truly fails to go the distance.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/mile-22-movie-review-mark-wahlberg-710675/|title=\u2018Mile 22\u2019 Review: Mark Wahlberg Action Thriller Feels Like \u2018InfoWars: The Movie\u2019|first=David|last=Fear|date=August 16, 2018|accessdate=August 21, 2018|work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n\n==Future==\n''Mile 22'' is intended to be a starting point to a multi-media series:{{Update inline|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Web series===\nAfter its release, [[STX Entertainment#STXdigital|STX Digital]] announced that they will produce a short-term live-action series called ''The Kiev Exchange''. The series will follow the CIA's elusive paramilitary force, Ground Branch, as they negotiate a tense and complex hostage exchange in a public square. Berg will return to direct, and it will be written by Umair Aleem, with the film's producers returning to produce the series, which is expected to be released sometime in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/04/stxsurreal-virtual-reality-ed-helms-dave-bautista-peter-berg-kevin-smith-jay-and-silent-bob-1202358602/|first=Anita|last=Busch|title=STXSurreal Unveils Development Slate With Ed Helms, Dave Bautista, Peter Berg, And Kevin Smith\u2019s \u2018Jay And Silent Bob\u2019|accessdate=June 11, 2018|date=April 4, 2018|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref>{{Update inline|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Possible sequel===\nThere are also plans for a sequel in the early stages of development.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/mile-22-sequel-black-list-writer-pen-mark-wahlberg-movie-1123165|first=Mia|last=Galuppo|title=Mile 22' Sequel in the Works With Black List Writer (Exclusive)|date=June 25, 2018|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=July 28, 2018}}</ref>{{Update inline|date=March 2020}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|4560436}}\n* {{Metacritic film|mile-22|Mile 22}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|mile_22|Mile 22}}\n* {{Mojo title|mile22|Mile 22}}\n\n{{Peter Berg}}\n\n[[Category:2010s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:American action thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Films about the Central Intelligence Agency]]\n[[Category:Films about terrorism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Mark Wahlberg]]\n[[Category:Films set in Asia]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Colombia]]\n[[Category:STX Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Techno-thriller films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Peter Berg]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2018 film directed by Peter Berg}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Mile 22\n| image          = Mile 22.png\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Peter Berg]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Peter Berg\n* [[Mark Wahlberg]]\n* Stephen Levinson\n}}\n| screenplay     = [[Lea Carpenter]]\n| story          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Graham Roland]]\n* Lea Carpenter\n}}\n| based on       = \n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* Mark Wahlberg\n* [[Iko Uwais]]\n* [[John Malkovich]]\n* [[Lauren Cohan]]\n* [[Ronda Rousey]]\n* [[Nikolai Nikolaeff]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Jeff Russo]]\n| cinematography = Jacques Jouffret\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* Colby Parker Jr.\n* Melissa Lawson Cheung\n}}\n| studio         = {{ubl|[[STX Entertainment|STXfilms]]|[[Huayi Brothers|H. Brothers]]|The Hideaway Entertainment|[[Donald Tang|Tang Media Productions]]}}\n| distributor    = [[STX Entertainment]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|8|17|United States}}\n| runtime        = 94 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $35\u201360 million<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/mile-22-mark-wahlberg-1202908708/|title=Box Office: Mark Wahlberg\u2019s \u2018Mile 22\u2019 Picks Up $1 Million on Thursday Night|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|first=Brent|last=Lang|date=August 17, 2018|accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=DEADwknd2/>\n| gross          = $66.3 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |title=Mile 22 (2018) |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=mile22.htm |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[IMDb]] |accessdate=November 21, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Mile 22''''' is a 2018 American [[espionage]] [[action film|action]] [[thriller film|thriller]] film directed by [[Peter Berg]] and written by [[Lea Carpenter]], from a story by Carpenter and [[Graham Roland]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shanley|first1=Patrick|title=Mark Wahlberg Action Film 'Mile 22' Gets July Release|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/mark-wahlberg-action-film-mile-22-gets-july-release-1084594|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=February 13, 2018|accessdate=February 25, 2018}}</ref> The film stars [[Mark Wahlberg]], [[Iko Uwais]], [[John Malkovich]], [[Lauren Cohan]], and [[Ronda Rousey]]. It follows an elite CIA task force composed of paramilitary officers from Ground Branch of [[Special Activities Division]], that has to escort a high-priority [[asset (intelligence)|asset]] 22 miles to an extraction point while being hunted by the government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://washingtontimes.com/news/2018/aug/14/peter-berg-asked-mark-wahlberg-to-tap-into-bannon-/|first=Douglas|last=Ernst|date=August 14, 2018|title=Peter Berg asked Mark Wahlberg to tap into \u2018Bannon intensity\u2019 for \u2018Mile 22\u2019|work=[[Washington Times]]|accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.traileraddict.com/mile-22/featurette-ground-branch|title=Mile 22 Featurette - Ground Branch (2018)|date=August 12, 2018 |work=Trailer Addict|accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref> The film marks the fourth collaboration between Berg and Wahlberg, following ''[[Lone Survivor]]'', ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]'', and ''[[Patriots Day (film)|Patriots Day]]''. \n\nThe film was released in the United States on August 17, 2018, and grossed $66 million worldwide. It received generally unfavorable reviews from critics, who called it \"confusing and a chaotic mess,\" alongside criticizing the cinematography and editing in the action sequences, although the performance of Uwais received praise.<!--cited in Reception-->\n\n==Plot==\n[[CIA officer]] and former [[U.S. Marine]] [[Force Recon]] [[veteran]], James Silva, leads a [[Special Activities Center|Special Activities Division]] team code-named Overwatch to raid a Russian [[Federal Security Service|FSB]] safe house in the United States. Under the remote supervision of James Bishop and his team, the mission is to locate and destroy shipments of [[caesium]] before the highly radioactive substance can be weaponized. In the ensuing firefight, most of the Russians and Overwatch operative Greg Vickers are killed, and critical intelligence on the caesium is destroyed. Silva executes the last survivor, a teenager who warns him that he is making a mistake.\n\nSixteen months later, in the [[Southeast Asian]] country of [[List of fictional countries|Indocarr]], police officer Li Noor surrenders himself at the US Embassy to negotiate for passage out of the country in exchange for information. Noor is revealed to be the asset of Overwatch agent Alice Kerr and reveals he possesses a disc containing information on the caesium, and is able to negotiate passage out of the country in exchange for unlocking the disc, which is programmed to self destruct within eight hours. Ambassador Dorothy Brady is visited by the country's Deputy Foreign Minister and state intelligence agent Axel, with the two demanding that Noor be handed over as he is wanted for [[espionage]]. Meanwhile, Noor fends off an assassination attempt by disguised government agents in the embassy infirmary using his skills as a former member of the elite tactical squad. \n\nWanting access to the intel, Silva's team is instructed to take Noor to an airplane at an airstrip 22 miles away, being provided with remote assistance from Bishop's team in [[Colombia]]. En route they are attacked by a group of men on motorcycles, who use a brief camera blackout to plant a bomb on one of the vehicles. During the ensuing gunfight, operative Sam Snow is mortally injured, and sacrifices herself to buy the group time. Taking cover in a restaurant, they are again attacked by Axel's men, in which Silva is saved by Noor and operative William \u201cDougie\u201d Douglas is seriously injured. The group retreats into an apartment complex, and Douglas sacrifices himself by putting down cover fire. Inside the building, Alice becomes separated from Silva and Noor, but is able to escape harm by using grenades and is later saved by Noor. Axel attempts to stop their car from reaching the airstrip, but is killed by Bishop's team via a [[drone strike]]. Arriving just before the plane takes off, Noor and Alice board the aircraft, with Alice having been given time off to see her estranged daughter. Noor provides Overwatch with the passcode to access the disk, with the intel appearing to be legitimate locations of the caesium. \n\nNoticing that the password \"rozhdestvo111\" matches the address of the FSB safehouse at the start of the film which was Christmas 111, Bishop comes to the conclusion Noor has betrayed them, and is actually acting as a [[triple agent]] for the [[Russian government]]. The mission is compromised.  A team [[Beriev A-50]], led by Senior Lieutenant Aleksander Aslanov, breaches the CIA's secure communications and control room. The teenager killed by Silva at the safehouse is shown to be Anatole Kuragin, the son of high ranking government official Vera Kuragina, who ordered the operation and sought personal revenge against the group. She hired Noor to serve as Alice\u2019s informant so they would trust him and activate Overwatch.  The purpose of Noor's unique negotiation has been to reveal the ultimate depths of the CIA special teams.  On the plane, Noor disarms a guard and breaches the cockpit, as revealed by communications from the plane. Alice\u2019s fate is uncertain. The team in Colombia, having been traced by the Russians, are gunned down, with a critically injured Bishop barely escaping. Having been unable to stop what occurred, Silva tells of his experience during a post-mission debriefing. Returning to his apartment, he puts up a picture of Noor on his wall, vowing revenge.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Mark Wahlberg]] as James Silva / \"Child 1\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Check out the first images and poster for Mark Wahlberg's Mile 22|url=http://www.joblo.com/movie-news/check-out-the-first-images-and-poster-for-mark-wahlberg-s-mile-22-135|website=[[JoBlo.com]]|publisher=Joblo Media|date=April 24, 2018|first=Kevin|last=Fraser|accessdate=May 7, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Lauren Cohan]] as Alice Kerr / \"Child 2\"<ref name=\"Cast\">{{cite news|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/mile-22/273474/mile-22-trailer-release-date-cast-story-details-and-set-visit|title=''Mile 22'' Trailer, Release Date, Cast, Story Details, and Set Visit|website=Den of Geek!|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|date=June 28, 2018|accessdate=July 2, 2018|last=Crow|first=David}}</ref>\n* [[Iko Uwais]] as Li Noor<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[John Malkovich]] as James Bishop / \"Mother\"<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[Ronda Rousey]] as Samantha \"Sam\" Snow / \"Child 3\"<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[Nikolai Nikolaeff]] as [[Army ranks and insignia of the Russian Federation|Senior Lieutenant]] Aleksander Aslanov<ref>{{cite web |title=Interview: Actor Nikolai Nikolaeff |url=https://reeltalker.com/2018/05/30/interview-actor-nikolai-nikolaeff/ |website=Reel Talker |date=May 30, 2018 |first=Jim |last=Alexander |accessdate=July 31, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Carlo Alban]] as William \"Dougie\" Douglas III/ \"Child 4\"<ref name=\"slashcast\">{{cite web |last1=Giroux |first1=Jack |title=\u2018Mile 22\u2019 Set Visit: Mark Wahlberg and His Team Get Sh*t Done |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/mile-22-set-visit/ |website=[[/Film]] |date=June 5, 2018 |accessdate=July 31, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Terry Kinney]]<ref name=\"firstcast\">{{cite web |last1=Billington |first1=Alex |title=Official Trailer for Gritty Action Movie 'Mile 22' with Mark Wahlberg |url=http://www.firstshowing.net/2018/official-trailer-for-gritty-action-movie-mile-22-with-mark-wahlberg/ |date=May 15, 2018 |website=FirstShowing.net |accessdate=July 31, 2018}}</ref> as Johnny Porter\n* [[Poorna Jagannathan]]<ref name=\"firstcast\"/> as Ambassador Dorothy Brady\n* Sam Medina as Axel<ref name=\"slashcast\"/>\n* Natasha Goubskaya as Vera Kuragina\n* David Garelik as Anatole Kuragin\n* Alexandra Vino as Sergeant Thomas<ref name=\"firstcast\"/>\n* [[Cedric Gervais]]<ref>{{cite tweet|title=In theaters August 17th #mile22|user=CedricGervais|first=Cedric|last=Gervais|number=1025119374959620096|date=August 2, 2018|accessdate=August 2, 2018}}</ref> as Greg Vickers / \"Child 5\"\n* [[CL (singer)|Chae Rin Lee]] as Queen<ref>{{cite web | url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3048287 | title=CL to play a killer in upcoming film | work=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]] | date=May 18, 2018 | last=Sung |first=Ji-eun | accessdate=August 10, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Emily Skeggs]] as M.I.T.\n* [[Peter Berg]] as Lucas\n* [[Lateef Crowder]] as Liam\n}}\n\n== Production ==\nOn March 2, 2015, it was announced that [[Ronda Rousey]] and [[Iko Uwais]] were set to star in the action-thriller film ''Mile 22'' scripted by [[Graham Roland]], with [[Peter Berg]] attached as producer. WME Global was in talks to finance the film.<ref name=Mar2015Variety>{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Ronda Rousey, Sam Medina, Peter Berg and Iko Uwais Team on Action Pic \u2018Mile 22\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/ronda-rousey-peter-berg-and-iko-uwais-team-on-action-pic-mile-22-exclusive-1201319883/|accessdate=October 27, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=March 2, 2015}}</ref> On July 2, 2015, [[Mark Wahlberg]] was cast in the film to play the male lead role, while Berg was also confirmed to direct the film for [[STX Entertainment]]. Berg would also produce the film along with Wahlberg and Stephen Levinson.<ref name=Jul2015THR>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title=Mark Wahlberg, Peter Berg Teaming Up for STX Action Movie 'Mile 22' (Exclusive)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/mark-wahlberg-peter-berg-teaming-806603|accessdate=October 27, 2015|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=July 2, 2015}}</ref> On March 28, 2017, Wahlberg and Berg announced that they are moving ahead with ''Mile 22'' as a trilogy of films.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Mark Wahlberg, Peter Berg Plan to Make Action Movie \u2018Mile 22\u2019 a Trilogy|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/mark-wahlberg-action-movie-mile-22-stx-1202017981/|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=March 28, 2017|accessdate=February 21, 2018}}</ref> On November 7, 2017, [[Lauren Cohan]] was cast in the film.<ref name=\"CohanCast\">{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title='Walking Dead' Star Lauren Cohan Joins Mark Walhberg in Action Movie 'Mile 22'|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/walking-dead-star-lauren-cohan-joins-mark-walhberg-action-movie-mile-22-1055807|accessdate=November 8, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=November 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Principal photography]] on the film was shot in [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] in November and December 2017 under the working title ''Ground Branch Triple'',<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hensley|first1=Ellie|title=Report: Mark Wahlberg, Ronda Rousey movie to film in Atlanta|url=https://bizjournals.com/atlanta/news/2017/09/21/report-mark-wahlberg-ronda-rousey-movie-to-film.html|newspaper=Atlanta Business Chronicle|publisher=[[American City Business Journals]]|date=September 21, 2017|accessdate=February 21, 2018}}</ref> and in [[Colombia]] in the capital city [[Bogot\u00e1]] and its surroundings in January and February 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mark Wahlberg y John Malkovich est\u00e1n en Bogot\u00e1 para rodar una pel\u00edcula |url=http://www.eltiempo.com/cultura/cine-y-tv/pelicula-de-john-malkovich-y-mark-wahlberg-que-sera-grabada-en-bogota-175480 |trans-title=Mark Wahlberg and John Malkovich are in Bogot\u00e1 to shoot a movie |newspaper=[[El Tiempo (Colombia)|El Tiempo]] |language=es |date=January 29, 2018 |accessdate=February 20, 2018}}</ref> On February 5, 2018, [[President of Colombia|Colombian President]] [[Juan Manuel Santos]] showed up during filming at one of the locations in Colombia. Director Peter Berg even had President Santos try to shoot one of the action sequences of the film.<ref>{{cite news|title=Santos turns up during Bogot\u00e1 shoot of \"Mile 22\" starring Mark Wahlberg|url=https://thecitypaperbogota.com/bogota/santos-turns-up-during-bogota-shoot-of-mile-22-starring-mark-wahlberg/18949|author=The City Paper Staff|newspaper=The City Paper Bogot\u00e1|date=February 5, 2018|accessdate=February 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThe final trailer was released online on July 26, 2018.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Foutch | first1=Haleigh | title=Final \u2018Mile 22\u2019 Trailer Teases Mark Wahlberg & Peter Berg\u2019s Action-Packed Thriller | date=July 26, 2018 | url=http://collider.com/mile-22-trailer/ | website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |publisher=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex Media]] | accessdate=July 31, 2018}}</ref> The film was originally going to be released on August 3, 2018, but was pushed back two weeks to August 17, 2018.\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Mile 22'' grossed $37.6 million in the United States and Canada, and $28.7 million in other territories, for a total worldwide gross of $66.3 million.<ref name=BOM/>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, ''Mile 22'' was released alongside ''[[Alpha (2018 film)|Alpha]]'', and was projected to gross around $17 million from 3,520 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-box-office-opening-fandango-presales-online-buzz-1202445334/|title=\u2018Crazy Rich Asians\u2019 Could Hit $30M In 5-Day Opening; Fandango Presales Currently Besting \u2018Girls Trip\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |date=August 14, 2018 |first=Anthony |last= D'Alessandro |accessdate=August 14, 2018}}</ref> It made $5.3 million on its first day, including $1 million from Thursday night previews at 2,600 theaters. It went on to debut to $13.6 million, finishing third at the box office.<ref name=opening>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-wednesday-opening-box-office-1202446094/|title=\u2018Crazy Rich Asians\u2019 Even Richer On Saturday With $10M+; Weekend Bling Now At $25M+ With $34M 5-Day Debut|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |date=August 19, 2018 |first=Anthony |last= D'Alessandro |accessdate=August 19, 2018}}</ref> In its second weekend the film dropped to sixth place, making $6 million.<ref name=DEADwknd2>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/melissa-mccarthy-happytime-murders-crazy-rich-asians-meg-weekend-box-office-1202451694/|title=\u2018Why \u2018Happytime Murders\u2019 Reps A Solo Career B.O. Low For Melissa McCarthy In A \u2018Crazy Rich\u2019 Weekend \u2013 Update|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |date=August 26, 2018 |first=Anthony |last= D'Alessandro |accessdate=August 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 23% based on 169 reviews, with an average rating of 4.1/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Mile 22'' lets the bullets fly\u2014and not much else\u2014in a thrill-deficient action thriller whose title proves sadly fitting for a film that feels close to a marathon endurance test.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/mile_22/|title=Mile 22 (2018)|publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating to reviews, the film has a weighted average score of 39 out of 100, based on 32 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/mile-22|title=Mile 22 Reviews|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=August 27, 2018}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B\u2212\" on an A+ to F scale, while [[PostTrak]] reported filmgoers gave it a 63% positive score.<ref name=opening/>\n\nThe performance of Uwais received some praise. Katie Walsh of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' said, \"As a performer and fight choreographer, Uwais delivers, with some extremely athletic and imaginative kills, mostly performed while handcuffed. It's also far and away Uwais's best acting performance in a film, and he almost makes ''Mile 22'' worth it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-mile-22-review-20180816-story.html|title=Review: Peter Berg and Mark Wahlberg pack action-thriller \u2018Mile 22\u2019 with maximum overkill|first=Katie|last=Walsh|date=August 16, 2018|accessdate=August 21, 2018|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> Brian Lowry of [[CNN]] stated, \"In fact, Uwais' action sequences\u2014fast paced and electric\u2014are easily the highlight of a movie otherwise characterized by an abundance of automatic-weapons fire and tedious dialogue during the fleeting gaps between those bursts.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/16/entertainment/mile-22-review/index.html|title='Mile 22' loads up brutal action vehicle that misses the mark|first=Brian|last=Lowry|date=August 16, 2018|accessdate=August 21, 2018|work=CNN Entertainment|publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref> David Fear of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the film 2 out of 5 stars, criticizing the editing of the fight scenes and stating, \"Why go through the trouble of giving Iko Uwais several fight scenes and editing them so that you can barely see the star inflict highly choreographed damage?...''Mile 22'' can give you chase scenes and bullet-ridden shoot-outs and evil Russians and lengthy diatribes. It can give you something approximating action. What it can't give you is a watchable action movie. That's where it truly fails to go the distance.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/mile-22-movie-review-mark-wahlberg-710675/|title=\u2018Mile 22\u2019 Review: Mark Wahlberg Action Thriller Feels Like \u2018InfoWars: The Movie\u2019|first=David|last=Fear|date=August 16, 2018|accessdate=August 21, 2018|work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n\n==Future==\n''Mile 22'' is intended to be a starting point to a multi-media series:{{Update inline|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Web series===\nAfter its release, [[STX Entertainment#STXdigital|STX Digital]] announced that they will produce a short-term live-action series called ''The Kiev Exchange''. The series will follow the CIA's elusive paramilitary force, Ground Branch, as they negotiate a tense and complex hostage exchange in a public square. Berg will return to direct, and it will be written by Umair Aleem, with the film's producers returning to produce the series, which is expected to be released sometime in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/04/stxsurreal-virtual-reality-ed-helms-dave-bautista-peter-berg-kevin-smith-jay-and-silent-bob-1202358602/|first=Anita|last=Busch|title=STXSurreal Unveils Development Slate With Ed Helms, Dave Bautista, Peter Berg, And Kevin Smith\u2019s \u2018Jay And Silent Bob\u2019|accessdate=June 11, 2018|date=April 4, 2018|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref>{{Update inline|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Possible sequel===\nThere are also plans for a sequel in the early stages of development.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/mile-22-sequel-black-list-writer-pen-mark-wahlberg-movie-1123165|first=Mia|last=Galuppo|title=Mile 22' Sequel in the Works With Black List Writer (Exclusive)|date=June 25, 2018|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=July 28, 2018}}</ref>{{Update inline|date=March 2020}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|4560436}}\n* {{Metacritic film|mile-22|Mile 22}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|mile_22|Mile 22}}\n* {{Mojo title|mile22|Mile 22}}\n\n{{Peter Berg}}\n\n[[Category:2010s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:American action thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Films about the Central Intelligence Agency]]\n[[Category:Films about terrorism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Mark Wahlberg]]\n[[Category:Films set in Asia]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Colombia]]\n[[Category:STX Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Techno-thriller films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Peter Berg]]\n", "name_user": "Creepee0", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammatical correction.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mile_22"}
